<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LARGE deal in the traded options sector boosted turnover, enlivening an
otherwise featureless day in the derivatives markets, writes Joel Kibazo.
Following light dealing at the opening, traded options were featured by a
big trade in British Petroleum when broker Strauss Turnbull, said to have
been acting for Lehman Brothers, 'crossed' 20,000 of the July 160 calls.
There was speculation in the market that the deal had been carried out for
tax purposes.
British Aerospace was the second most active stock option with 1,909
contracts dealt, BZW being a strong buyer of the November 260 calls, the
day's busiest series. Total turnover in traded options reached 46,759
contracts, with 5,002 lots transacted in the FT-SE 100 option.
In stock index futures, the FT-SE contract for September delivery
experienced a volatile session. With economic worries continuing,
independent traders led the contract down and it fell to a day's low of
2,411.
Bargain hunters prompted a turnround and, by noon, September had reached its
peak of 2,440 before drifting back. It finished at 2,424, up 8 from the
previous close but 7 points below its estimated fair value premium to cash
of about 18. Turnover, at 8,120 contracts, was reasonable.
