<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Baghdad's defiance of UN team raises possibility of
air-attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, Middle East Correspondent and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN AIR-STRIKE by the Gulf war allies against targets in Iraq is more likely
now than at any time since the war because of Baghdad's defiance of United
Nations weapons inspectors, US and British officials said yesterday.
But Iraq's UN ambassador said dropping 'a bomb or two' on Baghdad or any
other city would not force his country to let the weapons inspectors search
its agriculture ministry.
Diplomats at the UN said there was unanimity among the 15 members of the
Security Council that Iraq could not be allowed to get away with barring the
weapons team from a ministry building in Baghdad. In the face of increasing
harassment, relays of inspectors have parked outside the building for 17
days.
The US, Britain and France have begun consultations on possible use of force
unless Iraq yields.
The revival of a serious military option follows growing concern and
frustration, not just at Iraq's defiance of the inspectors, but also at
other rebuffs to the UN and a spate of attacks on UN guards in northern
Iraq.
Furthermore, US officials said the Security Council was determined not to be
seen as a pushover during tense operations in Cambodia and the former
Yugoslavia. 'The council is not at this point going to allow itself to be
regarded as a pussycat,' one diplomat said.
Sir David Hannay, British ambassador to the UN, said publicly on Monday that
military action against Iraq had not been ruled out. In private, British
officials said UN patience with Iraq was running out. They believe an
air-strike could be made without further UN resolutions.
Nevertheless, US and British diplomats in New York shied away from reported
comments by an anonymous Security Council diplomat suggesting that a strike
against Iraq was 'inevitable' and would take place within 10 days.
Dismissing the military threat, Mr Abdul Amir Al-Anbari, Iraq's ambassador,
told reporters: 'The use of force would undermine the authority of the
council because, I tell you, it is not going to change the Iraqi position.
'Throwing a bomb or two, whether on Baghdad or here or there, is not going
to change (matters). To the contrary, it shows that the council, without the
co-operation of the Iraqi government, cannot do much.'
The raised tension came amid unconfirmed reports that Iraqi president Saddam
Hussein had been assassinated. The reports, filed originally by the Egyptian
Middle East News Agency, were apparently prompted by interruption in normal
service on Baghdad radio yesterday morning, when programmes were replaced by
readings from the Koran. But normal service resumed yesterday afternoon and
there was nothing to confirm the rumours.
The real issue in Iraq, Page 17
</TEXT>
