<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Council mortgage scheme launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL tenants will soon be able to convert rent payments into part
ownership of their homes, according to a government consultation paper
published yesterday, Bethan Hutton writes.
The rents-to-mortgages scheme, a manifesto promise, is aimed at
local-authority tenants in England and Wales who cannot afford to exercise
their full right to buy.
Under the scheme's proposals, tenants will be able to take out a mortgage on
an equity share of their homes, with repayments equal to, or greater than,
their current rent. They will also be entitled to a discount on the purchase
price, in proportion to the amount of equity they take on. The remaining
equity share will stay in the hands of the local authority but can be bought
out later.
Sir George Young, the housing minister, launching the scheme at an Institute
of Housing seminar, said it would extend choice and opportunity for local
authority tenants. 'It could offer them a way of using money they would have
given to the landlord to acquire a stake in their home,' he said.
The scheme is likely to form part of a Housing, Land and Urban Development
bill in November.
</TEXT>
