<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / When the best of friends turn to foes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON APRIL 10 the editors of the Tory tabloids were invited to celebrate Mr
John Major's election victory at a party in 10 Downing Street. Just three
months later the newspapers' fury over the prime minister's support for new
legal curbs on their reporting has sparked a state of virtual war.
It was Lord MacAlpine, a long-time Conservative fund raiser, who declared
that Sir David English of the Daily Mail, Sir Nicholas Lloyd of the Daily
Express and Mr Kelvin MacKenzie of The Sun were the real heroes of Mr
Major's campaign. Few who saw the bouts of panic that had gripped officials
at central office as polling day approached doubted his judgment.
The three tabloids were relentless in selling the central Tory message: that
Labour would preside over a big increase in taxes and that Mr Neil Kinnock
could not be trusted to run the country. Lurid front pages provided daily
advertisements for the Conservative cause.
Each of the editors was in constant touch with the senior ministers running
Mr Major's campaign. On more than one occasion the message the newspapers
delivered to Mr Major was that his strategy was a shambles. But they
remained fiercely loyal.
If Mr Major thought the tabloids' performance up to April 9 guaranteed him
an easy ride once he returned to Downing Street, he was soon disabused of
the idea. Within a matter of weeks the tabloids were reminding him that the
rules which operated during election campaigns did not apply in the long
intervals between them.
The Express and London's Evening Standard, another staunch supporter,
infuriated the prime minister by taking up the cause of the Tory
Euro-sceptics after the Danish voters had rejected the Maastricht treaty.
The Standard, and to a lesser extent, The Sun, joined a campaign against Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, over his failure to pull the economy from
recession.
But it is the issue of press privacy - now entangled with the allegations
about Mr David Mellor's personal life - which has sparked the most serious
rift. The seeds were planted last month when a book about the marriage
difficulties of the Prince and Princess of Wales provoked a flood of
speculative stories in the tabloids.
Mr Major, whose frequent contacts with the royal family are often
overlooked, was furious. The revelation a few weeks later that the first
child of Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, had been born before
she married added to his anger. The result was a decision to refer again the
issue of personal privacy to an inquiry headed by Sir David Calcutt QC. But
Mr Major made clear that he had decided in his own mind that the tabloids'
excesses should be curbed by legislation to prohibit intrusions into the
personal lives of the royals and other public figures.
That message - delivered in an informal chat with a political correspondent
during an overseas visit - infuriated the editors who had backed him during
the election. Mr Paul Dacre, the newly appointed editor of the Daily Mail,
sought to warn off the prime minister in a full page editorial. The Sun
emblazoned its pages with the same message.
Scandals sell newspapers and editors are judged on their circulation
figures. But no one at Westminster guessed that Mr MacKenzie would respond
to Mr Major's anger over the publicity surrounding Mr Mellor with quite such
a devastating charge against an unnamed cabinet minister. If the allegation
is proved - and the editor has so far said he will not name names - then the
culprit will be forced to resign. The message for Mr Major is that best
friends can often make the worst enemies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
