FT  22 JUL 92 / Management training record mixed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST British companies believe money spent on management training is money
well spent but only half are doing any formal training, according to a
survey published yesterday.
The survey was by the government-backed Management Charter Initiative, which
seeks to improve standards of management training. It found that companies
employing more than 500 people had the most managers involved in training
while small companies were less actively engaged in formally training
managers.
Mr Andrew Summers, chief executive of the MCI, said one reason might be that
small companies could spare less time for managers to be away from work.
Training, he said, should not consist just of sending people on courses.
According to the survey of more than 500 organisations, smaller companies
were least likely to agree that training increased loyalty or management
standards were useful in measuring performance.
The business services sector trained more managers than any other, while the
machinery, manufacturing and engineering sectors were least likely to be
training them.
The MCI, through local organisations including Tecs and chambers of
commerce, is seeking to influence more companies to improve training.
Management Development in the UK. MCI, Russell Square House, 10-12 Russell
Square, London WC1B 5BZ. Pounds 35.
