<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / One-stop ticket towaste land renewal: Plans to aid
inner-city developers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN important feature of the new Urban Regeneration Agency (URA), according
to environment secretary Mr Michael Howard, will be its ability to offer a
one-stop service to developers who wish to invest in the UK's inner cities.
The URA will have powers to assemble parcels of land - if necessary by
compulsory purchase - and clear them for developers. It will control two
sources of government funding: derelict land grant, which is used for land
reclamation; and city grant, which is available for pump-priming development
of inner-city sites by the private sector.
English Estates, the quango that builds factories and offices in the
assisted areas, will also be absorbed into the URA, so that the agency can
tempt businesses into needy areas by providing premises.
The initial response to yesterday's consultation paper from the
professionals involved in inner-city regeneration was positive.
Mr Gerald Cary-Elwes, secretary general of the British Urban Regeneration
Association, said: 'The idea of a one-stop agency for identifying and
assembling packages of land which can be used for development is excellent.
'The URA follows the very successful pattern of similar organisations in
Wales and Scotland. It would be wonderful if Peter Walker, who will be the
chairman of the new agency, could repeat the success of his work in Wales.'
However, there will be disappointment if the URA is no more than a land use
agency.
'Urban regeneration is about more than just land and property development,'
believes Mr Victor Hausner, a consultant involved in many inner-city
regeneration schemes. 'It involves economic regeneration, training, housing
improvements and so on.'
Pulling together all those other elements at present means tapping into the
long list of government-backed organisations that can supply these other
elements of urban regeneration:
The 16 task forces run by the Department of Trade and Industry which are
responsible for stimulating enterprise and training people for new jobs.
Most local training is the responsibility of the 82 Training and Enterprise
councils under the employment department. In Scotland, the task falls to
Local Enterprise Companies. But the education department is in charge of
city technology colleges, which are supposed to concentrate educational
resources in urban areas.
Housing needs are dealt with by programmes to rehabilitate run-down housing
estates, such as Estate Action and the Priority Estates Project. If the
developer intends to provide low-cost social housing, local housing
associations will need to be involved.
The Home Office Safer Cities project encourages building, design and
employment initiatives to reduce crime.
An early port of call would have to be the local council. Of the 57 urban
priority areas, 31 have now won more than Pounds 1bn of government funds for
urban regeneration over the next five years from the City Challenge
programme.
Also indispensable in the eight cities where they exist are the City Action
Teams. These are led by different government ministers, which co-ordinate
the various inner-city initiatives and programmes run by different
government departments. And if there is an urban development corporation, it
 -rather than the URA - will be the organisation to turn to for development
needs.
The complexity of the arrangements has been repeatedly criticised by the
Audit Commission, the local-government watchdog. Having described the
programmes as a 'patchwork quilt' in a 1989 report, the commission said in
1991 that the quilt 'remains only loosely sewn together'.
It was that fragmentation that led to the introduction last year of City
Challenge, the bidding process that aims to bring together resources from
all the different programmes and concentrate them on projects proposed by
local partnerships between the public and private sector.
'City Challenge offers a multi-faceted solution to a multi-faceted problem,'
says Victor Hausner. 'The challenge for the URA will be to see whether it
can develop a comprehensive strategic approach in the same way as City
Challenge.'
The government is not unaware of the challenge. The Conservative election
manifesto included a promise to bring resources for targeted inner-city
programmes into a single budget. One way of doing so would have been to use
the URA as the organisation through which to focus the plan, perhaps by also
giving it responsibility for managing City Challenge.
However, yesterday's consultation paper says merely that the government is
'developing' its proposal to integrate inner-city regeneration funds. For
the moment, the agency will be yet another partner to be drawn into
inner-city programmes, rather than a one-stop solution to the developer's
problems.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
