<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Police authority agrees Halford settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERSEYSIDE Police Authority yesterday agreed to the early retirement on
health grounds of Ms Alison Halford, an assistant chief constable who said
she had been the victim of sex discrimination.
The authority said that Ms Halford, 52, would get 'the usual pension, to
which she has contributed, payable in such circumstances'. She will receive
a lump sum of Pounds 142,600 and an annual pension of Pounds 35,836.
As a result of the settlement, Ms Halford will withdraw allegations of sex
discrimination against Sir Philip Myers, inspector of constabulary for the
north-west; Mr James Sharples, chief constable of Merseyside;
Northamptonshire Police Authority and the home secretary. It is expected
that the sex discrimination case - which has been supported by the Equal
Opportunities Commission - will be formally withdrawn when the industrial
tribunal hearing it meets in Manchester today.
Mr David Henshaw, clerk of Merseyside Police Authority, said disciplinary
proceedings against Ms Halford would automatically cease as a result of her
retirement. She has been suspended from duty for the past 19 months after
allegations of misconduct arising from a swimming incident at the home of a
Merseyside businessman while she was duty officer in charge of the force.
A meeting of the police authority last Friday that had been expected to
approve terms for ending the case was adjourned, and yesterday the authority
agreed to the settlement only by 10-8 with three abstentions.
Some members left the meeting saying they believed the disciplinary process
against Ms Halford should have gone ahead. Others were concerned that the
effect on the EOC's budget may have been a factor in pressure for a
settlement.
Pressure for a negotiated settlement to the case had grown with the
knowledge that Home Office ministers were becoming concerned about its cost.
They were referring to the financial cost - at least Pounds 1m and set to
double if the industrial tribunal hearing which started in May had
continued. Ministers must, however, have been even more anxious about the
police service, already damaged by a series of miscarriages of justice.
Evidence from the opening weeks of the tribunal hearing left an impression
of police life at extreme variance to the professionally managed public
service that the government and senior officers are trying to create.
Ms Halford, the first woman to reach the rank of assistant chief constable
when appointed to the Merseyside force eight years ago, failed in nine
subsequent attempts for further promotion. She claimed that the failures
were a result of sex discrimination and began her industrial tribunal
action.
Mr Eldred Tabachnik QC, for Ms Halford, told the opening of the tribunal
that her professional competence and commitment to the job were beyond
challenge. But the 'woefully inadequate and ramshackle' promotion system to
which Ms Halford was subjected, suggested Mr Tabachnik, provided fertile
ground for 'personal dislike, prejudice, hostility and personal
discrimination to flourish'.
The tribunal then heard Ms Halford describe Sir Kenneth Oxford, her former
chief constable at Merseyside, as having a management style that was 'plain
outright rude'. She claimed he had treated her like a dog, describing him as
aggressive and dogmatic. Mr Sharples, the present chief constable, was
described by Ms Halford as having been devious and two-faced. It is not
unknown for industrial tribunals to hear such antagonistic evidence after a
breakdown in workplace relationships. Some of the evidence in the Halford
case, however, was on a different level - claims of a conspiracy involving
the special branch and the home secretary to bug Ms Halford's office and
home telephone.
Ministers will be relieved that yesterday's agreement removes the prospect
of further such allegations.
The settlement will not please those in the police service who saw the
tribunal as an opportunity for its promotion procedures, particularly as
they affect women, to be exposed to public examination. Women officers
complain that they were until recently prevented from undertaking many
operational roles - denying them the full range of experience needed for the
highest posts - and that they are disadvantaged by the service's macho
values.
The state of relationships between Ms Halford and her Merseyside colleagues,
whatever the cause, always made it unlikely that the tribunal could become a
forum for the calm examination of such topics. Even before the case reached
the tribunal, Ms Halford had been suspended from duty on disciplinary
grounds - an action later set aside by the High Court - and subsequently
suspended again.
The question of whether sex discrimination prevented one of the most senior
women ever to have served in the British police getting to the very top
remains unanswered.
</TEXT>
