FT  22 JUL 92 / Owner-managers' optimism faulted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES that are owner-managed expect to achieve an average 4.8 per cent
growth over the next 12 months, says a survey of 900 businesses by Mori for
accountants Ernst and Young.
Such confidence by owner-managers reveals a 'disturbing expectation gap'
given economic forecasts of zero or negative growth over the same period,
Ernst and Young said.
The firm urged realism: 'We suspect that the estimates are based on hope
rather than hard evidence. Forecasts that cannot be supported will undermine
confidence among companies' financiers.'
A total of 63 per cent of owner-managed businesses thought the economy would
improve over the next year and 66 per cent said the election result had
increased confidence. The companies surveyed all had annual sales of between
Pounds 5m and Pounds 100m - those with sales of more than Pounds 50m were
most likely to think the economy would improve.
Managing in a Zero Growth Economy, Ernst and Young, Becket House, 1 Lambeth
Palace Road, London SE1 7EU. Free.
</TEXT>
