<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Anger at funeral of Mafia's victims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE PEOPLE of Palermo yesterday vented their anger and frustration over the
state's inability to curb the ever more brazen power of the Mafia.
Crowds jostled, jeered and insulted Mr Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, the Italian
president, Mr Giuliano Amato, the prime minister, and police chiefs as they
attended the funeral of five bodyguards assassinated on Sunday in Palermo
alongside Mr Paolo Borsellino, the leading anti-Mafia magistrate.
The crowd's frustration was also reflected in a potentially more awkward
move for the government. Seven of the 16 junior judges in Palermo working on
Mafia-related cases announced they were resigning. At the same time, Mr Aldo
Rizzo, mayor of Palermo, handed his resignation.
It was the second time in two months that government members have been
abused by hostile crowds at funerals of magistrates and policemen murdered
by the Mafia. The last occasion was the funeral of Mr Giovanni Falcone,
whose three-car armoured convoy was destroyed by a powerful bomb on May 23
outside Palermo.
Yesterday the mood was uglier and more frustrated over the authorities'
failure to prevent the car bomb attack on the bodyguards and Mr Borsellino -
a man known to have become the prime target for the Mafia.
Some 10,000 people gathered outside Palermo cathedral. A heavy police cordon
finally broke and people rushed inside at the end of the service.
The president and government members had to leave by a side entrance, their
escort scarcely able to hold back the jostling crowd.
The government's hostile reception occurred despite rapid action in
despatching nearly 3,000 extra police and troops to the island. The
government also promised to toughen existing anti-Mafia laws going through
parliament, and set in motion a large-scale plan of transferring imprisoned
Mafia bosses to high security jails on the mainland and on an isolated
island off Elba.
