<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: US economy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve Board Chairman, looks like a man
determined to keep his options open. Those looking for hints of further
easing in yesterday's congressional testimony may draw some satisfaction
from his admission of disappointment with the pace of economic recovery in
the second quarter. The same goes for the assertion that US inflation is to
sink to a level lower than has been sustained for 25 years. Those expecting
no change in policy will point to the forecast of increased economic
momentum and the excuse, in the form of changed velocity, for money supply
growth stuck below target.
The Fed may now be in a reactive mode in which it will ease policy again if
the recovery does not pick up over the summer. But implicit in Mr
Greenspan's remarks is a degree of doubt on whether a further fall in short
term rates would help. The real need is to keep long term rates headed lower
to encourage mortgage refinancing and ease the burden of consumer debt. If
Mr Greenspan's natural inclination yesterday was to reassure the politicians
about growth, he will also have been anxious to ensure that the markets
heard his message on inflation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
