FT  22 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bitter Harvest, tonight's Screenplay (BBC2 at 9.00pm) is a tale of murder,
exploitation, and British West Indians in search of their 'roots', filmed in
the sugar cane fields of Dominica.
This week's Fighting Back could be riveting. TV producer Desmond Wilcox
describes his heart-bypass and peers at someone else on the slab undergoing
the same op. (Do the people cut up nightly on screen for our delectation
receive appearance fees?)
The World in a Garden (C4 at 8.30pm) begins a four-part series describing
the restoration of a Victorian garden at Biddulph Grange, Staffordshire.
E. Nesbit's Edwardian classic, Five Children and It is being repeated (BBC 1
at 5.05pm). In case you were wondering, It is a furry creature, the
Psammead. Worth capturing on video, in case the summer hols are rained off.
The comedy film Gung Ho (BBC 1 at 10.25pm), made in 1986, centres on the
clash between American and Japanese values in the work-place. It stars
Michael Keaton (alias Batman) as foreman of a car-plant who acts as cultural
go-between.
