<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Radical shake-up at TUC urged by 'super-unions'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A THOROUGH rationalisation of the Trades Union Congress, promised for years
but never delivered, has come a step closer.
The AEEU engineering and electrical union has called for a 'radical
reassessment' of the organisation in a motion tabled for this year's TUC
congress.
Leaders of the growing number of 'super-unions' complain that the TUC
duplicates services they provide. They believe the cost of the organisation
can no longer be justified while trade union membership is falling.
They also say that its role as the labour movement's alternative civil
service, and lobbyist of government, has become obsolete.
The AEEU says resources should be concentrated on four areas: health and
safety, education and training, European and international lobbying and
co-ordination of union submissions to government.
The TGWU general union, Britain's biggest, has also submitted a motion
calling for a refocusing of the TUC's role. Congress is likely to consider
amalgamating the two motions.
Previous moves to reform the TUC have been frustrated by the inability of
union leaders to agree over which of its functions should be dropped. But
the Conservative general election victory and the recession have lent
urgency to the debate. The TUC is already reducing costs, mainly through job
cuts.
Almost 40 jobs, out of 250, are being phased out but even after this
reduction staff numbers will still be at 1979 levels, when total trade union
membership was more than four million higher than it is today.
It is understood the TUC accepts the need for reform and does not view the
moves by the AEEU and the TGWU as unhelpful.
The AEEU emphasises its motion should not be interpreted as a obituary for
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary. The TGWU's motion was seen by some
as a direct attack on Mr Willis's leadership.
</TEXT>
