FT  22 JUL 92 / Debt collectors to seek new legal role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEBT recovery companies are to seek approval to represent their clients in
legal cases which are usually handled by solicitors.
About 80 debt recovery companies met in Birmingham on Monday to launch the
iniative and to form an Institute of Licensed Debt Practioners as a
professional organisation supervising debt collection practices.
The organisation will ask Lord Mackay of Clashfern, the Lord Chancellor, for
authority to launch a legal service so that clients can choose between the
traditional route through solicitors and employing a qualified debt recovery
company representative.
Debt recovery companies see similarities between their position and
conveyancers'. It is no longer necessary to employ a solicitor to handle the
legal details of a property purchase.
The Lord Chancellor's department said Lord Mackay would soon issue a
consultation paper on the way in which civil enforcement agents - bailiffs
and sheriffs - go about their business and whether any changes in the law
are necessary.
