<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Sotheby's will sell Thurn und Taxis treasures: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOTHEBY'S is to sell works of art from the collection of the Prince of Thurn
und Taxis - one of the finest private art collections in the world - and
hopes thereby to begin to restore its flagging fortunes.
Johannes, 11th Prince von Thurn and Taxis, died suddenly in December 1990,
leaving a nine-year-old heir, Prince Albert. Death duties have forced the
family to value its collection and to sell works of art, which are expensive
to maintain and offer no income, rather than the family's land and
industrial holdings.
The collection is mainly housed at Regensburg in Bavaria, and incorporates
art and furnishings from the 25 castles the family disposed of between 1920
and 1970. The Thurn und Taxis fortune is traced back to the 15th century,
when Franz von Taxis established the first postal service in the Holy Roman
Empire.
The first auction, to be held in Geneva on November 16 and 17, will include
jewels, silver, and works of art. It is expected to raise Pounds 8m,
although with the art market depressed, Sotheby's has set very modest
estimates. The actual total raised for works of exceptional provenance and
rarity may be much higher.
Among the most desirable lots are two rare 18th-century diamond and emerald
pendants bearing the insignia of the Order of the Golden Fleece, valued at
Pounds 300,000 and Pounds 100,000, and the pearl and diamond tiara
commissioned by Napoleon III on his marriage to the Empress Eugenie in 1853.
It is composed of precious stones and pearls from the French State Treasury
and carries a conservative estimate of Pounds 100,000.
A jewelled and hardstone snuff box created for Frederick the Great about
1760 is estimated at Pounds 800,000. Among the silver, the most expensive
item should be a silver gilt ewer and salver made in Augsburg around 1740 by
Johann Christoph Stenglin: it carries an estimate of up to Pounds 280,000.
Sotheby's expects to organise more sales from the collection over the next
few years: the extent of the family's tax demands have yet to be finalised.
There might also be a wish to raise money for Prince Albert's two sisters. A
sum of Pounds 40m has been estimated for the eventual realisation of the
dispersal, although the 500-room castle at Regensburg will remain full of
treasures.
At Sotheby's in London yesterday, an auction of English literature totalled
Pounds 589,655 but was 37 per cent unsold, confirming that the recession is
affecting sections of the art market traditionally dominated by serious
collectors and immune to setbacks.
</TEXT>
