<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 92 / Owner-managers' optimism faulted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES that are owner-managed expect to achieve an average 4.8 per cent
growth over the next 12 months, according to a survey of 900 businesses
conducted by Mori for accountants Ernst and Young.
Such confidence by owner-managers reveals a 'disturbing expectation gap,'
given economic forecasts of zero or negative growth over the same period,
Ernst and Young said.
The firm urged companies to be realistic: 'We suspect that the estimates are
based on hope rather than hard evidence. Forecasts that cannot be supported
will undermine confidence among companies' financiers.'
A total of 63 per cent of owner-managed businesses thought the economy would
improve over the next year and 66 per cent said the election result had
increased confidence. The companies surveyed all had annual sales of between
Pounds 5m and Pounds 100m - those with sales of more than Pounds 50m were
most likely to think the economy would improve.
In spite of forecasts for growth, businesses expected staffing levels to
remain constant, suggesting that productivity remains below desired levels,
according to Ernst and Young. 'If output does not increase sufficiently, or
possibly even if it stays constant, staffing levels could be reduced
further,' the survey found.
The majority of businesses (68 per cent) said their financial goals had
remained unchanged over the past six months and they had no plans to raise
additional finance. Ernst and Young questioned whether businesses would be
able to increase output from existing resources.
In general, the businesses surveyed found their banks helpful, although
banks in the Midlands were seen as less helpful than elsewhere.
Manufacturing companies also viewed their bankers as less helpful than
businesses in the retail, distribution and service sectors.
Managing in a Zero Growth Economy, July 1992 survey. Ernst and Young, Becket
House, 1 Lambeth Palace Road, London SE1 7EU. Free.
</TEXT>
