<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Kohl 'the key' to farm deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY's Chancellor Helmut Kohl is the 'key' to brokering a farm trade
accord enabling a breakthrough in the long-delayed Uruguay Round of talks on
world trade liberalisation, according to Sir Christopher Prout, European
Parliament vice-president.
Noting the Uruguay round was now 'in crisis,' Sir Christopher told a
conference in London on free trade it was 'absolutely crucial' for the
west's recession-troubled economies to clinch a deal, and that Chancellor
Kohl was the only European leader able to press the French government to
make compromises on cuts in subsidised farm exports.
He conspicuously omitted Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission President,
as a potential broker, presumably because of 'institutional deadlock in the
EC system itself' over farm reform. Also omitted was Mr John Major, prime
minister of UK, which is currently occupying the EC presidency. Mr Major
failed at the recent summit in Munich of the G7 industrial countries to
force a compromise.
'The key lies with Chancellor Kohl. He is the one man who can press
President Mitterrand to give the necessary number of metres to clinch the
deal. He has shown no inclination to press Mitterrand, but is going to have
to do so,' he said.
Sir Christopher was fiercely critical of the 'prehistoric' consensus
decision-making process on EC farm policy, which he blamed for blocking
reform. He called either for the introduction of majority voting on
agriculture, or for responsibility for farm policy to be transferred away
from Brussels and back to national governments.
He also warned that Uruguay Round aims to liberalise trade could be
frustrated by exchange rate manipulation, and said a supra-national currency
arrangement would be needed 'if a Gatt-type multilateral trade agreement is
to be sustained'.
</TEXT>
