<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TURNOVER in the derivatives market soared on the back of strong two-way
business in both stock index futures and traded options, as economic worries
led to a sharp retreat, writes Joel Kibazo.
The September futures contract on the FT-SE, having opened at 2,415, was
gently squeezed forward and had risen to 2,436 by around 10am. However, with
continuing worries about the economy and an indication from the Alliance &amp;
Leicester Building Society of a possible increase in mortgage rates, the
initially positive mood changed, causing the September contract to fall
sharply, which in turn pulled the underlying cash market lower.
At the day's worst, around 1pm, September, which had dropped to 2,367, was
trading at parity with the cash index.
The intervention in the money markets to support the dollar provided the
spur for a recovery in the contract in the afternoon. September finished at
2,416, down 22 from the previous session and around 5 points below its
estimated fair value premium to cash of about 18; volume reached a hefty
14,000 contracts.
Turnover in traded options was also high, totalling 50,180 lots by the
close. The FT-SE option was particularly active, having 26,313 contracts
transacted, while the Euro FT-SE option saw 4,677 lots dealt.
</TEXT>
