<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Huge operation to save dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR rose nearly four pfennigs from its low against the D-Mark
yesterday after concerted central bank intervention stopped a probable
free-fall of the US currency, writes James Blitz.
For the first time in more than a year, the US Federal Reserve and most of
Europe's central banks acted in unison to buy dollars as the currency
dropped to DM1.4463, a hair's breadth from its historic low of DM1.4430.
The decision to intervene at around 3pm London time also supported sterling
and the Italian lira by weakening the D-Mark. The fall of the pound and the
lira had, until then, been raising ever wilder rumours about a possible
realignment of the European Monetary System.
Analysts in London said the operation, which must have involved the purchase
of hundreds of millions of dollars, was a success as far as the
dollar/D-Mark rate was concerned. The dollar ended at DM1.4815 after a
previous DM1.4610 close, as dealers heeded that the Fed had abandoned the
policy of 'benign neglect' of the currency.
Central bank intervention has been well respected by the market since the
1980s, and dealers are unlikely to go short of dollars again at around
DM1.4500. In New York the US unit further rallied to finish at DM1.4935.
Dealers still found reasons to be bearish. The fundamental factors that have
kept the D-Mark strong still exist. The fear that the Bundesbank will put up
its emergency Lombard rate to control its money supply problem hangs over
the market. The yawning differential between German and US interest rates
will continue to drive the temptation to buy D-Marks. And it is not in the
US authorities' long term interest to promote an expensive dollar, following
June's trade deficit that exceeded Dollars 7bn.
There are also doubts about the strength of sterling and the Italian lira.
Although the pound rallied to a high of DM2.8530 following the intervention,
it dropped back to close at DM2.8425, down  1/2 pfennig on the day. Mr Neil
MacKinnon, chief economist at Yamaichi International in London, said: 'The
devaluation tag still hangs over the pound, and the Bank of England may have
to intervene again.'
The prognosis for the lira also remains gloomy. Before the concerted
intervention began, the Bank of Italy was heavily intervening in the market,
as its currency slipped to L762 to the D-Mark. It eventually closed at
L760.30.
Traders believe the policy of raising the discount rate, which the Italians
have done by 1.75 percentage points in the last fortnight, may fail to check
the currency's fall. By lifting rates, the Italians are increasing the cost
of financing their budget deficit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
