<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Transamerica plans to drop
non-life insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSAMERICA, the San Francisco-based financial services group, plans to
pull out of the property-casualty insurance business. The company said
yesterday it had called in Morgan Stanley and Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
two Wall Street investment banking firms, to advise on the disposal of its
non-life insurance division.
Transamerica added that it would consider either selling the operation,
'demerging' it through a free distribution of shares in the insurance
division to Transamerica shareholders, or floating the business on the stock
market.
The news sent Transamerica's shares sharply higher in a plunging stock
market; in late trading the shares were Dollars  7/8 higher at Dollars 45
3/8 . Transamerica's insurance group is based in Woodland Hills, California,
and ranks as the 27th largest property-casualty insurer in the US, in terms
of net written premiums.
It made after-tax profits of Dollars 63m in 1991, including investment gains
of Dollars 6m. Its revenues were Dollars 2.2bn, and assets stood at Dollars
4.6bn.
However, the subsidiary increased reserves in the second quarter, mainly to
back its workers' compensation and entertainment insurance operations.
Because of this, it is expected to make an operating loss of Dollars 40m in
the second quarter.
Transamerica said the move would allow it to concentrate on 'less cyclical,
higher-returning finance and life insurance activities'.
'We face demands for increased capital to support growth in many of our
businesses,' said Mr Frank Herringer, chief executive. 'In view of these
demands, we have elected to focus our resources on our life insurance and
finance businesses.'
Transamerica added that it did not expect to realise any significant gain or
loss on the disposal.
The remaining operations have assets of about Dollars 30bn, and made
after-tax profits of Dollars 71m in the first quarter.
The company said its continuing operations should also have a strong second
quarter, more than doubling the Dollars 43.6m reported in the same period of
1991.
</TEXT>
