<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Dofasco chief quits over
strategic planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DOFASCO, Canada's biggest steelmaker, has parted company with its chairman
and chief executive amid mounting public criticism of his management style
and his role in Dofasco's ill-fated acquisition of Algoma Steel five years
ago.
Dofasco said yesterday that Mr Bill Wallace resigned as a result of
'differences over how to best implement the company's new strategic plan.'
A spokesman declined to elaborate, but insisted that the plan, which
includes an emphasis on flat-rolled products and the study of mini-mill
opportunities, will remain intact.
Mr Wallace had worked for Dofasco for 36 years, but took over as chairman
only two months ago. Tensions over his position were clear at the company's
most recent annual meeting where a group of dissident shareholders
challenged his nomination to the board of directors.
Ms Margaret Cornish-Kehoe, analyst at ScotiaMcLeod in Toronto, claimed
yesterday that Mr Wallace 'didn't have people skills and was very closely
associated with Algoma'.
Mr Wallace's departure appears to reflect intense soul-searching over the
future of Dofasco, considered one of North America's premier steel producers
until its costly purchase of Algoma in 1987.
Three years later. Dofasco wrote off its entire CDollars 713m (USDollars
594m) investment in the troubled Ontario-based company, which itself is
Canada's third biggest steel producer.
Mr Wallace spearheaded the Algoma acquisition, but has always insisted that,
in keeping with Dofasco's collegial management style, the decision to go
ahead was a joint one.
The financial burden of Algoma has been exacerbated by the recession.
Dofasco suffered a CDollars 25m loss last year and a further loss of
CDollars 17.8m in this year's first quarter.
Mr Wallace's place as chairman will be temporarily taken by Mr Jack Leitch.
</TEXT>
