<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Aquascutum wins cash injection
from Renown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RENOWN, Japan's biggest clothing maker, is injecting Pounds 8m (Dollars
15.28m) into Aquascutum, its upmarket British fashion retailer. The UK
business has been dragged into losses by the effect of recession on luxury
goods sales.
The move comes two years after Renown paid Pounds 74m to take over the
company. It is the latest case of a celebrated brand name requiring further
cash infusions by a new foreign owner. The sum, although modest, is being
paid at a time when the parent is itself in the red. Aquascutum's pre - tax
losses for the 1991 calendar year reached Pounds 13.47m on sales of just
Pounds 42.30m, and Renown expects the offshoot will stay in loss this year.
Of the extra funding, Pounds 4m was paid in May and the rest would be
provided next January, Renown said. The capital injection will help meet
Aquascutum's commitments in projects such as refurbishing its Regent Street
flagship store in London and opening an outlet in North America.
Renown, a producer of mid-market ready-to-wear apparel, is to begin selling
Aquascutum lines in Japan from next month, spending Y2bn (Dollars 16m) on a
specialist store for the brand. This had not been possible until the recent
unwinding of a licensing arrangement between Aquascutum and Mitsubishi Corp,
which had given the latter distribution rights for the country.
Aquascutum says its sales in Japan should reach Y10bn in Renown's accounting
year, which begins in February. However, such a performance would come in
the face of the country's own economic downturn, which has quelled the
enthusiasm of metropolitan Japanese for foreign designer labels.
Indeed, some retail sector analysts had thought the change might prompt
shoppers to trade down to the more affordable lines mass-produced by Renown.
However, any such trend remains unreflected in the parent company's
performance. Renown said its pre-tax loss for a seven-month interim period
which ends in 10 days would exceed the Y11bn it had previously forecast. It
blamed the setback on poor sales, particularly at the department stores it
supplies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12030</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAE7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Bank of America declines 11.8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK OF America has blamed special charges related to its recent takeover of
Security Pacific for an 11.8 per cent decline in second-quarter net
earnings. The bank is now the second largest in the US, with Dollars 188.6bn
of assets.
The results - the first since the merger was completed on April 22 - were
hit by a net Dollars 181m of non-recurring items, including Dollars 395m of
merger-related restructuring write-offs and a Dollars 157m gain on an asset
sale.
Because of the charges, Bank of America's net profit in the quarter was
Dollars 240m, compared with Dollars 272m a year ago.
Earnings per share were 63 cents, compared with Dollars 1.16. The bank said
its earnings per share would have been Dollars 1.19 but for the one-time
charges, while its net income would have been Dollars 421m.
The bank stressed that the results were not comparable with results in the
same period of last year. However Mr Richard Rosenberg, chairman, said he
was pleased with the progress in integrating Bank of America and the former
Security Pacific.
Wall Street also seemed satisfied with the report: the bank's share price
was marked Dollars 2 7/8 higher to Dollars 44 3/8 .
Mr Rosenberg said efforts to achieve operating cost savings in connection
with the merger were going well. The bank was also focused on credit
quality, 'especially in light of the current difficult economic
environment', he said.
Bad debt provisions in the second quarter amounted to Dollars 240m against
Dollars 175m a year ago. For the first six months of 1992, these provisions
totalled Dollars 470m, compared with Dollars 320m in the first half of 1991.
Non-performing assets were Dollars 4.56bn at the end of last month,
reflecting the problems among combined assets of both banks; the same
measure for Bank of America alone was Dollars 3.08bn a year ago.
Net loan losses amounted to Dollars 194m, up from Dollars 169m a year ago.
The second-quarter 1992 losses consisted of Dollars 402m of write-offs and
Dollars 208m of recoveries. The write-offs were related mainly to credit
card and other consumer loans, and the recoveries mainly to the sale of
sovereign debt and recoveries on previous write-offs.
Net income for the first six months of 1992 was Dollars 543m, down from
Dollars 554m in the same part of last year.
At the end of last month, the new group had 88,000 employees, or some 4,700
fewer than the combined total level a year ago at Bank of America (54,100)
and at Security Pacific (38,600).
Net interest income after bad debt provisions was Dollars 1.44bn, compared
with Dollars 916m a year ago for Bank of America alone.
Non-interest income was Dollars 1bn, including a one-time gain of Dollars
157m related to the sale of Bank of America's payroll processing business.
The figure a year ago for the bank alone was Dollars 595m.
At the end of last month, Bank of America had Dollars 4.4bn of assets to be
disposed, composed primarily of former Security Pacific loans, investments
in subsidiaries and operations, foreclosed property and other assets deemed
non-strategic.
</TEXT>
