<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / UK Company News: Getting back to basics to resume growth -
Henry Barrett looks to its core businesses to achieve a recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT A difference recession makes. Two years ago Henry Barrett Group, the
steel and industrial fasteners company, was still riding high, having grown
rapidly since flotation in 1987.
The Bradford-based group benefited from the last construction boom and
bought 13 companies in the late 1980s. Now it is incurring losses and is
heavily burdened by debt, in spite of having sold several of those
acquisitions.
Henry Barrett shares have fallen from their 1989 peak of 280p to 20p, and
the market value has dropped from a high of Pounds 110m to less than Pounds
9m.
The problems were precipitated by the collapse in demand for steel-framed
warehouses and out-of-town stores from retailers such as B&amp;Q, MFI and Texas
Homecare.
Henry Barrett's biggest mistakes, however, came from its attempts to
diversify away from the inevitably cyclical core business of steel
stockholding, and building steel-framed buildings.
In 1988 it bought Park Pallet, a company making carrying systems for
automated warehouses and factories, and the following year purchased OSS and
ASS, which make shelving storage and handling systems for big retailers.
Mr James Barrett, a director from the group's founding family, said: 'The
materials handling business suffered from a slowdown in the retail sector,
so proved to be in the same cycle as construction.'
These companies have now been sold, as have two more profitable acquisitions
 -BNL, which makes thermoplastic bearings, and Lurmark, which manufactures
spray nozzle tips, mainly for use in agriculture.
Mr Barrett said the underperformance of the materials handling businesses
was initially masked by the strength of the group's core activities.
However, even successful acquisitions, such as BNL and Lurmark, took up a
disproportionate amount of management time.
He concludes: 'We can make our business more resilient by staying within our
area of expertise, rather than running around to find something to be good
at.'
Not all is gloom at Bradford, however. One surprise has been the continuing
resilience of steel stockholding, which grew directly from the iron
merchant's business founded by the original Henry Barrett in 1866.
Despite the recession, the stockholding side has continued to trade
profitably and expand market share. It is one of the leading independent
steel stockholders in the UK. The group is big enough to negotiate keen
prices for steel, but its 10 existing depots serve local markets right down
to small workshops, and can make good margins.
Mr Barrett said: 'When we are in a position to grow, that is what we will
grow.' The group still has no depots in Wales, Scotland or south of the
Thames.
Henry Barrett's best short-term hopes for recovery lie in its construction
divi-sion, as the continuing attrition of competitors raises the prospects
of higher prices and a recovery in profit margins.
Westbury Tubular Structures, purchased in 1989, continues to trade
profitably and has just completed a Pounds 4m contract for the roof of the
new Waterloo Channel tunnel terminal in London. In May the workforce was
reduced by 36 to 80, but order intake since then has been good.
On the design and build side, the group is now trading at about break-even,
having closed its Leicester factory in November with the loss of 50 jobs.
The business now employs 205 people - 175 in Bradford and 30 on the sales
side.
Mr Barrett said: 'There's a market of about 250,000 tonnes a year of the
single-storey structures we make for industrial and retail use. We need
about 20,000 tonnes of that to keep going. Prices are currently at Pounds
650 a tonne, compared with up to Pounds 1,100 at the peak. We just need a
small recovery in prices to make profits.'
The widespread demise of competitors is finally allowing prices to move up,
but the group has also succeeded in raising productivity by 15 per cent a
year. Just-in-time manufacturing techniques have cut stocks from seven to
two weeks, with increased flexibility. The group completed erection of a
15,000 sq ft baggage handling facility at Heathrow within 23 days of
receiving the order.
The construction division's main headache lies with Don Reynolds Holdings,
which makes flat-panel cladding for use in steel-framed buildings and was
bought for Pounds 10.8m in 1989.
Demand for its product in the UK has collapsed, partly because fewer offices
and business parks are being built, and also because the fashion has
switched back towards more traditional materials, as championed by the
Prince of Wales.
DRL's best hope of profits lies overseas, through joint ventures in Japan,
the US and continental Europe. The loss-making UK operation is now sharing
its factory with Lindapter, a profitable business which sells a system for
joining steel without bolts or welding, and exports half its output.
Mr Donald Parvin, who became Henry Barrett's chairman in December, assumed
an executive role earlier this month. Mr James Barrett will no longer act as
group chief executive, but will concentrate on the stockholding division. Mr
Barrett's younger brother, Richard, is managing director of the construction
division.
A former chief executive of Matthew Clark, the mechanical and electrical
engineers, Mr Parvin said he believed a cut in working capital and greater
efficiency could yield better financial results - even in present trading
conditions.
Henry Barrett is expected to make a pre-tax loss of about Pounds 3m on
turnover of Pounds 100m in the current year, and is likely to break even
next year.
Overshadowing the whole group's future are its borrowings of between Pounds
17m and Pounds 18m, which puts gearing at about 75 per cent. Mr James
Barrett conceded: 'Until we reduce that debt, our share price will
languish.'
Mr Parvin said Barclays, the group's bankers, had been very supportive. Its
financial advisers, NM Rothschild, were looking at possible steps to
strengthen the balance sheet, but had so far made no definite proposals.
The sale of surplus property could raise a few millions, but the chairman
said one way forward could be to form strategic alliances with one or more
overseas steelmakers - from the US, Europe or Japan.
Mr Parvin said Henry Barrett had always bought steel from overseas. In
exchange for a cash injection, such producers could gain from Henry
Barrett's knowledge of and access to the UK market.
James and Richard Barrett borrowed heavily to help buy out the 48 per cent
of the shares held by family members and bring the company to market. What
lessons have they learnt from its subsequent roller-coaster ride? James
said: 'We can't eliminate the cyclicality of design and build, because that
is how people expand. But in such a violently cyclical business, you really
need an ungeared balance sheet at the start of any downturn.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
