<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Marine Midland turnround raises earnings to Dollars 41m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MARINE Midland, Hongkong and Shanghai Bank's US subsidiary, yesterday
reported a turnround to net earnings in the second quarter of Dollars 41m
(Pounds 21m) from losses of Dollars 37m for the same period of 1991.
The result takes half-year profits to Dollars 43.6m against first-half
losses in 1991 of Dollars 109.3m.
Mr John Bond, president and chief executive officer, said: 'We are
encouraged by the continuing improvements in credit quality and operating
margins.' The bank's earnings were improved by non-recurring loan recoveries
and sales of foreclosed property.
Marine Midland was acquired by Hongkong Bank during the 1980s. On two
occasions since, the bank was forced to make capital injections totalling
Dollars 500m into its US subsidiary to shore up its balance sheet.
Marine was one of New York's main money centre banks, but it was hit badly
by its exposure to less developed country (LDC) debt in the early 1980s and
by its exposure to the US property market in the last half of the 1980s.
It has now given up its aim of being a money centre bank and has
repositioned itself as a provider of retail banking services and finance to
small and medium-sized companies.
Signs of improvement in Marine Midland's performance - the result of cost
cutting and a contraction in its balance sheet - began to show through last
year when losses were pared to Dollars 23.8m in 1991 from Dollars 164.3m in
1990. In the first quarter of this year it made a profit of Dollars 2.6m.
The bank said that during the second quarter it achieved improvements in net
interest margins and further reductions in expenses.
Net interest income was Dollars 178.9m, compared with Dollars 168.3m in the
first quarter. Operating expenses, excluding restructuring and
credit-related costs, were Dollars 173.8m against Dollars 179.7m in the
first quarter.
Observer, Page 15
