<DOCNO>FT923-12038</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: Italy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The odds seem stacked against poor old Italy. Mr Giuliano Amato, the new
prime minister, talks bravely of curbing the budget deficit and privatising
sclerotic state industries. The reality is that there is no political
consensus behind reform. The Mafia seems to be doing its utmost to
destabilise the new government and the lira is trading close to its absolute
floor of L765 against the D-Mark, although the official discount rate has
been raised twice in the last month.
The exchange rate has come to symbolise Italy's ambition to be a part of
mainstream Europe. If Mr Amato cannot hold it, the danger looms of a return
to the dark days of the 1970s, characterised by impotent government,
repeated devaluation, inflation, capital flight and terrorist outrage.
Partly because the alternative is so grim, there is an outside chance that
Mr Amato may succeed. The rise in interest rates has opened up an 8
percentage point gap between short-term rates on the lira and the D-Mark.
That should be enough for the time being to make speculators think twice
about driving the lira below its floor. Maybe external pressure on the
currency, combined with the activities of the Mafia at home, will stiffen
popular resolve to accept change. Reform was never going to be anything but
messy - witness the outraged reaction to the government's wise decision last
Friday to wind up Efim, the loss-making state holding company.
Still, the task is a Herculean one. Each rise in interest rates pushes up
the cost of servicing the government's mammoth debt. To help sell its
treasury bills even at these higher rates, Mr Amato has already had to stoop
to the ruse of a special tax on bank deposits. That looks like the action of
a government running short of practical ideas. It hardly creates a
propitious climate for launching large scale privatisation issues in the
equity market.
If Mr Amato succeeds in staving off the lira's day of reckoning, Italian
equities will look cheap, especially after yesterday's 6 per cent fall. The
odds, however, are so long and the consequences of failure so dire that
international investors, who have been largely out of the market for the
past year, would do best to continue watching from the sidelines.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
