<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: More bears than traps
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's action by central banks to support the dollar was good news for
those who had begun to fear that international co-operation on currencies
was a thing of the past. But it raises two basic questions: whether the
initiative can be expected to stick: and if so, how far it addresses
preoccupations which have driven down world markets in the past few days.
There are those who argue that US and German interest rates are respectively
as low and as high as they are going to get. That could yet prove correct.
But it is worth asking how far the present parities have answered the policy
objectives in each country. The weak dollar was supposed to loosen monetary
conditions in the US and stimulate exports. Judging by last week's trade
figures, at least, it is scarcely doing its job. Equally, the high D-Mark
was supposed to tighten conditions in Germany. Judging by the latest money
supply figures, it is not working too well either.
Granted, the dollar's plunge to all-time lows against the D-Mark has been an
important element in the recent weakness of European markets. In a parochial
UK context, it is worth noting that, as the chart shows, London has been
moving closely in line with Continental markets ever since its post-election
peak. For other ERM members besides the UK, the combination of high German
rates and a weak dollar has had profoundly worrying implications for
corporate earnings and dividends.
It would also be wrong to push the parallels with the row between the
Bundesbank and the US Federal Reserve in 1987, which played an important
part in triggering Wall Street's historic collapse. Equity markets were then
screamingly high in relation to bonds, inflation was rampant and corporate
earnings were approaching their cyclical peak. In every respect, the
situation is now reversed.
But there are other forces afoot. Wall Street has been perceived as
overvalued for so long that one tends to forget that it is so in fact. Nor
is it quite clear how far the price allows for a Democrat in the White
House. Tokyo is back below 16,000 on the Nikkei, which poses a threat no
less real for being familiar. In Europe, the working assumption still is
that the Maastricht treaty will go ahead. But aside from the little matter
of the French referendum, it now looks not impossible that the unravelling
of Italy's finances will cause disarray in the ERM rather more immediately.
And from a UK viewpoint, it is not yet clear that a rise in interest rates
is off the cards. Besides the risk of an increase in the German Lombard
rate, the UK government's aggressive bidding for domestic savings may yet
force a general rise in the mortgage rate. It is also somewhat disquieting
that despite yesterday's sharp rise in the dollar against the D-Mark,
sterling ended the day lower against the D-Mark than it started.
In the end, one is left with the frustrating impression that world markets
are in the grip of large fundamental forces which as yet are imperfectly
identified. Since currencies are clearly part of it, it is much to be hoped
that yesterday's bear trap proves effective. But it will not do the job on
its own.
</TEXT>
