<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Kevin Maxwell ordered to pay Pounds 406m damages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KEVIN MAXWELL has been ordered by the High Court to make interim payments
totalling Pounds 406.8m to the liquidators of Bishopsgate Investment
Management, the company from which hundreds of millions of pounds of Maxwell
empire pension funds disappeared.
It is believed to be the largest damages award ever made against an
individual in the English courts.
The liquidators, Robson Rhodes, were given final judgment against Mr Maxwell
in an action in which they claimed Pounds 450m compensation or damages for
alleged breaches of his fiduciary duty as a director of BIM, which managed
pension funds for a number of Maxwell companies.
The full amount for which Mr Maxwell is liable has yet to be assessed. He
has said he is insolvent and wants to formulate proposals to put to his
creditors. However, the liquidators intend to force him into bankruptcy.
Because of his lack of resources, Mr Maxwell did not defend the case. Mr
Justice Mummery said that, on the liquidators' evidence, there was no
defence to their claims.
On Thursday the liquidators will ask the court for final judgment in an
identical action against Mr Maxwell's brother Ian.
After yesterday's ruling Mr Maxwell said in a statement that he had not
played an active part in the proceedings brought by the liquidators since
declaring himself insolvent on July 8.
On that day a High Court order, which expires tomorrow, was made preventing
his creditors bringing proceedings against him while he formulates proposals
to put to them. In spite of the order, the liquidators were given leave by
the court on July 10 to seek summary judgment against Mr Maxwell.
His statement continued: 'Had I had the resources, I would have strenuously
denied all allegations of breach of duty.' He said it remained his desire to
assist in the realisation of his assets for the benefit of all his
creditors.
Mrs Margaret Cole, of Stephenson Harwood, the liquidators' solicitors, said:
'It is our intention to seek Mr Maxwell's bankruptcy. We believe a trustee
in bankruptcy is the best person to investigate his assets and recover or
secure them for the benefit of all the creditors, of whom we are by far the
largest.'
At the end of a two-hour private hearing, Mr Justice Mummery gave his
decision in open court because of 'the widespread public interest in this
litigation'.
He said that the liquidators' 44-page claim related almost entirely to
alleged breaches of fiduciary duty by Mr Maxwell while a director of BIM.
The judge ordered an account to be taken of what was due from Mr Maxwell to
BIM and payment by Mr Maxwell of the sum found to be due.
Separate orders were made in respect of breaches of duty in 'procuring,
effecting and consenting to' specific transactions, coupled with orders for
interim payments.
The judge continued an order freezing Mr Maxwell's assets up to a maximum of
Pounds 450m.
Mr Kenneth Trench, chairman of the Maxwell Pensioners Action Committee,
said: 'Presumably this will bankrupt Mr Maxwell, and whether pensioners will
actually get more than it has cost them to obtain this court decision is
highly speculative.'
He said fees to professional advisers were depleting pension assets by
roughly Pounds 1m a month and urged the government to take over the cost of
pursuing assets through the courts.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
