<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Observer: Official text
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Not many companies see fit to publish a corporate history after just 15
years in business. Even so The Argyll Story, which is all about Britain's
third biggest grocery chain, the Safeway supermarket group, is unnecessarily
slim.
The unknown author could have made much more of the available material.
After all, the most famous thing most people remember Argyll for is its
ambitious Pounds 1.9bn bid for Distillers, a company more than three times
its size. This earns only one paragraph with a vague reference to 'the
intervention of Guinness' and Argyll's subsequent decision to withdraw from
the drinks business.
No mention, for example, of the resignation of James Gulliver, Argyll's
chairman, said by some never to have recovered from his failure to win
Distillers. It's tomes like this that give business biographies a bad name.
</TEXT>
