<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Observer: Right place, right time?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
John Bond, chief executive of the Hongkong Bank's Marine Midland subsidiary,
must be hoping that he is luckier than John Tugwell, chief executive of
National Westminster Bancorporation. Both men are the same age - 51 - and
were given the same task of sorting out their employers' wayward US banking
affiliates.
Both have only been doing the job for just over a year yet already seem to
be getting spectacular results. NatWest Bancorp bounced back from a loss of
Dollars 276m to a net profit of Dollars 66.1m in the first half, while
Marine Midland is also back in the black. Bad debts are falling and the
embarrassed parents are once again boasting of how well their US offspring
are doing.
But there the similarity ends. Despite the fact that NatWest Bancorp
probably posed a bigger challenge than Marine Midland, Tugwell knows that
however hard he tries he is unlikely ever to get a shot at the top job at
NatWest. That post was filled when young Derek Wanless leapfrogged
everybody.
However, Hongkong Bank's 61-year-old boss Willy Purves has promised to
appoint a new group chief executive soon. Marine Midland may be less
important than Malaysia, but it's the sort of high-profile job that catches
the eye of investors who don't know how to judge the depth of the Hongkong
Bank's management.
</TEXT>
