<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Mixed blessings for the three Ps: Patients have benefited
from the Citizen's Charter, but parents and passengers have not
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major certainly did not intend to undersell his Citizen's Charter
when he launched it in a white paper a year ago tomorrow. 'The Citizen's
Charter is the most comprehensive programme ever to raise quality, increase
choice, secure better value and extend accountability. It will ensure that
quality of service to the public and the new pride it will give to those who
work in the public services will be a central theme of government policy for
the 1990s.'
The prospectus bulged with more than 80 proposals for improving the UK's
public services, ranging from the privatisation of British Rail to a special
'chartermark' for public services which met the highest standards of
customer satisfaction. Users of public services were promised information
about the quality of service they were entitled to expect and power to
insist that performance targets were met.
The white paper was followed by the launch of a series of charters covering
different user groups. These range from the traveller's charter for people
passing through customs at ports and airports to the customer charter for
claimants using the social security benefits agency. The 20th charter, from
London Underground, was launched yesterday, with the usual combination of
performance targets and compensation for non-fulfilment.
Overseeing this process is a special Cabinet Office unit and a panel of
advisers chaired by Sir James Blyth of Boots. They know that central to the
success of the charter will be its progress in improving the lot of the
'three Ps': patients, passengers and parents.
The greatest impact has been made with the patient's charter, which promises
that no patient will have to wait more than two years for hospital treatment
once on a waiting list. More than 50,000 patients had been waiting for more
than two years in March 1991, a backlog which was virtually eliminated by
April 1992 when the charter was implemented.
Hitting that target required significant input of cash, with excess capacity
in private hospitals bought in to clear the more intractable waiting lists.
There were accusations at the time that this had been achieved by increasing
the lists of people waiting less than one year. However, Mr Brian Edwards,
general manager at Trent regional health authority who was seconded to the
department of health to lead the team setting up the charter, says that
achieving the target was long overdue.
'It had a marginal impact on people waiting less than a year,' he says, 'but
a great impact on some real people - including many children - who had been
waiting a very long time and whose needs were just as great.'
Mr Edwards notes other achievements, including quicker treatment of
emergency cases and reduced waiting times for out-patient appointments.
'Before, a few people were concerned about these aims,' he says. 'Now
everybody is focusing on them.'
British Rail's passenger's charter not only makes promises about
performance, it also offers compensation if targets are not met. For
commuters with season tickets, there will be rebates if trains fail to hit
reliability and punctuality targets over 12 months (the first rebates will
be payable in January 1993 after the scheme has been running for a full
year).
Ordinary passengers can also claim compensation in the form of vouchers
against the cost of future journeys if they are delayed by more than an
hour. This formalises the previous discretionary and unadvertised
arrangements under which more than Pounds 6m a year was paid out to
passengers who bothered to complain about delays. However, there have been
complaints that the scheme is too restrictive.
'Vouchers and petty discounts, to be used only in certain circumstances and
given grudgingly under a complex system of exemptions and conditions, go
nowhere near far enough,' according to Mr John Beishon, director of the
Consumers' Association. 'Neither is there any mention of consequential loss.
If a train is cancelled and you have to pay out for the cost of a taxi home,
BR shouldn't quibble about paying the cost.'
Offering the least by way of performance targets is the parent's charter.
Instead, this promises more information about schools and pupils' individual
performance, with more frequent inspection by independent inspectors. League
tables of schools' performance will be published from next year, including
data on truancy and success in getting pupils into higher or further
education. Here the emphasis is much more on providing parents with
information on which they can base choices of school, and to encourage
teachers to improve their performance.
Outside its three core areas, there have been problems in implementing some
of the white paper proposals. The Lord Chancellor's department has so far
failed to produce its justice charter to make the courts more user-friendly,
for example. And the deregulation of London Buses has been postponed at
least until 1994. Also stalled is the network of local lay adjudicators who
would take up complaints against public services and hand out small amounts
of compensation informally.
There is also a distinct impression that the charter is losing some of its
cachet. Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, might have taken
the opportunity of last week's announcement about privatising the Royal
Mail's parcel delivery service to mention it as an example of meeting
charter objectives on competition and improved services. But he chose not
to.
Nor did Mr John MacGregor when he published the white paper on the
privatisation of British Rail, although this was one of the firm proposals
in the charter white paper. If almost every government policy last year was
hung on the peg of the Citizen's Charter, it is now reserved for the
politically duller announcements such as market testing in the civil
service.
However, Mr William Waldegrave, the minister in charge of the charter,
asserts that it remains at the top of the government's priorities. Seminars
will be held every six months to keep ministers up to the mark on
implementing the charter. And Mr Waldegrave has promised a white paper on
progress in the autumn.
The prime minister has also given Mr Waldegrave a powerful weapon in the
right to veto colleagues' bids for extra funds for their departments to
improve customer service and implement charter promises. This implies that
his endorsement would bolster any such bid, something of a coup given the
jealousy with which the Treasury guards the spending round (though it
remains to be seen what this right is worth).
Nobody can now say that the charter was an election gimmick, but it has yet
to make a real impression outside a few limited areas. One year on, the
Citizen's Charter looks more likely to be a permanent feature, but its
political credibility still depends on the commitment of Mr John Major, its
'onlie true begetter'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12052</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAELFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Leading Article: The price is wrong
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
VIEWED FROM across the Atlantic, the US resembles a vast summer sale, where
prices of many internationally traded products are currently two-thirds of
those ruling in Europe. However, European visitors to the US should contain
their elation. The question they should be asking is why the prices they pay
at home are so high.
US price levels are not some short-lived freak occurrence. Only a small part
of the difference with, say, Britain is due to the recent weakness of the
dollar. Even with the pound at Dollars 1.50, the pre-tax price of many items
in the US would look like a bargain to a British tourist. In reality, a wide
range of goods has long been cheaper in the US than in Europe. Computer
buyers, for instance, have for many years paid the same number of pounds in
Britain as US buyers paid in dollars - almost irrespective of the prevailing
exchange rate. Though this anomaly has recently narrowed, it remains
perplexingly large.
One explanation is that some manufacturers have segmented world markets in
ways which enable them to charge higher prices in Europe than in the US.
Such practices have certainly been encouraged by the European Community,
which has sought to protect uncompetitive indigenous industries such as
electronics by bringing anti-dumping cases against a wide range of Japanese
exports. Since exporters frequently settle such cases by agreeing to raise
prices, they receive windfall profits which they can use to subsidise
cut-price competition elsewhere.
Wide discrepancies
Yet there are also wide transatlantic price discrepancies for many
manufactured products in which trade is not distorted by anti-dumping
actions, high tariffs or quotas. The puzzle is why these differentials are
not undermined by competition from cheaper 'grey' imports. Within the EC,
such cross-border arbitrage is explicitly blessed by Brussels, on the
grounds that that it speeds economic integration. However, the impact in
Europe of 'grey' imports from the US is still marginal.
Part of the reason lies in differences in technical specifications for
products such as cars and consumer electronics. Some stem from genuine
variations in national standards, but others are artificial barriers erected
by manufacturers. For instance, Japanese-made Nintendo video game machines
sold in Europe are programmed not to accept the software which Nintendo
sells in the US for half the price in Europe. Another obstacle is that many
manufacturers restrict the validity of extended guarantees to the country
where goods were purchased.
However, these limitations do not apply to products for which there is a
world standard and which require no after-sales service. Compact discs are a
classic example. A year's US output of CDs could be flown in a few jumbo jet
freighters from New York to London in seven hours. Yet European CDs are
still dearer than in the US.
Entry barriers
The reasons - in this and other cases - may have to do with the structure of
European retailing, where barriers to entry are generally higher than in the
US. Above all in Britain, where much of the trade is handled by relatively
few national chains. UK planning rules also favour incumbent operators by
severely limiting the amount of land available for retailing. As a result,
it tends to command premium prices, which have to be recouped through high
margins.
Furthermore, relations between retailers and manufacturers are far more
opaque in Europe than in the US. For instance, detailed trade prices of new
cars are freely available in the US. In Britain, it took a Monopolies and
Mergers Investigation to ferret them out.
While reliable information remains so sparse, it is hard to be sure of the
exact reasons for international price differentials. Their persistence in
supposedly global markets calls for searching investigation by EC and
national competition authorities. European consumers are entitled to clear
answers - not least because their readiness to spend their way out of
recession will be much reduced if they are compelled to pay through the
nose.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
