<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Arts: The Challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE quest for new life in the musical continues. The Mercury Workshop,
formed in April, is a group of songwriters committed to furnishing new work
for the musical stage, over two dozen of them. Their patron is Stephen
Sondheim, with whom many of them have studied.
This collective's first project, The Challenge, was given on Sunday night at
the Shaw Theatre, where it was handsomely performed and rapturously
received.
As The Challenge proceeded, I became reluctantly grateful for its
professionalism, for the fact that it relied little on scenic effects, and
for its intention to keep entertaining its audience by intelligent means.
The oddest feature of The Challenge is its subject. It tells the tale of
Daedalus, the arch-craftsman of mythological Crete, who:
constructed an artificial cow in whose framework Queen Pasiphae could
copulate with her husband Minos's prize bull;
planned the famous labyrinth which would hide the resulting progeny, the
monstrous Minotaur;
devised wings so he and his son Icarus could escape from Minos, but lost
Icarus, who flew too near the sun.
Needless to say, lyricists had a field-day with the dirty thoughts suggested
by Pasiphae and the bull. My loudest laugh came after Daedalus had used the
word 'lovable' to Pasiphae. Kit Hesketh-Harvey had her song: 'Love a bull?
Funny you should say that. . .'
Boy-girl romance has to wait till Theseus and Ariadne in Act Two, but then
receives a pretty flood of pop ardour with Eric Woolfson's 'If I ever see
that face again.' When they meet a second time they start to reprise this
tune but - felicitous touch - the chorus shut them up.
The Challenge doesn't relieve my gloom about the state of the musical,
because, like the rest of them, it just isn't musical enough. Still, in
every way it already surpasses dozens of musicals professionally presented
in recent years on either side of the Atlantic.
</TEXT>
