<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Arts: Gerry Mulligan Tentet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARRY BOOTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL-STAR gatherings often disappoint. The idea of several 'greats' all
swinging together in big bands is hard to resist and sells tickets. But the
promised synergy rarely materialises, as was the case on this last
star-studded night of the JVC Capital Radio Jazz Parade which featured The
Gerry Mulligan Tentet and the New York Jazz Giants.
Mulligan and his tentet are celebrating the legacy of the late Miles Davis
and The birth of the cool sessions in particular. 'The Cool' was born in
1948 in the hot basement room of a New York Chinese laundry where arranger
Gil Evans lived. He and Miles Davis were looking for a new sound which had
echoes of the Claude Thornhill orchestra for which Evans then arranged and
Mulligan played.
Most of the ingredients for a successful rebirth were in place at the
Festival Hall and Mulligan's big band is an inflated version of the Miles
Davis Capitol Band which recorded in 1949/50. The tentet retains the French
horn and tuba (Bill Barber was an original member) and adds a tenor. Lee
Konitz sits in his old place and, in Miles' stead, for the season's live
performances at least, there are the warm tones of Art Farmer. The old tunes
 -'Boplicity', 'Moon Dreams' and 'Jeru' - are interspersed with favourite
Mulligan and Farmer originals like 'The Flying Scotsman' and 'Blueport'.
Poor sound balance which washed out the subtle orchestral colours achieved
by Evans' arrangements and indifferent, sometimes sluggish playing from
Konitz conspired to disappoint, however.
The pleasure of hearing Mulligan's weaving and agile baritone is
undiminished, especially set against his old sparring partner Art Farmer's
flugelhorn. But the beauty of the short, sighing original arrangements for
the ten pieces needs a separation in sound which was lacking on Saturday
night and it took all of Mulligan's baritone torque to pull the ensemble
along.
Money might have been better spent on the recently released CD (The Rebirth
of Cool, GRP Records GRD-9679) which covers the old ground in studio
conditions.
The New York Jazz Giants, on first, suffered a similar problem with their
combination of standards and originals. Jon Faddis (trumpet), Bobby Watson
(alto sax), Lew Tabackin (tenor sax) and Mulgrew Miller (piano), with a
lively rhythm section, promised more than they could deliver in the face of
mushy sound quality.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
