<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / People: Continuity confirms Coyne at JCB
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Martin Coyne (above left) is taking over as chief executive at JCB
Excavators, the Staffordshire group which is one of the UK's largest
privately-owned businesses.
His accession is part of a reshuffle at the top of JCB, consequent upon the
retirement, after 30 years in the company, of Gilbert Johnston the
long-serving current chief executive.
Johnston becomes deputy chairman.
JCB, which places a premium on continuity, tends to fill its top jobs
internally so the appointment of Coyne does not presage a sudden shake-up.
Although Coyne is not interested in change for the sake of change, he notes
that 'this is very much a changing world; anyone not comfortable with change
is going to be in difficulties.'
Indeed, his road through JCB and his reputation in the company are
associated with new ventures. Now he is sponsoring internal innovation with
the introduction to JCB of its version of total quality management. Earlier
he had taken JCB into the mini-excavator market and forged a joint venture
with Sumitomo, the Japanese group.
Recently Japan has been playing a big part in his life. His son, a
biotechnology graduate, is teaching English in Japan. His daughter is
training to be an engineer.
Coyne, 52, is a graduate of Ford; he joined JCB in 1975, the same year that
Johnston became chief executive.
