<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Technology: The 'right' price to pay for a PC - Technically
Speaking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sharpest indictment of the computer industry's failure to persuade the
broader business community of the value of its products, in Europe if not in
the US, is the widely held conviction that there is suppressed demand for
PCs which will only be released when prices fall to the 'right' level.
It is more than a conviction; there is plenty of evidence from Amstrad's
success with its word processors that people are prepared to experiment with
an unfamiliar technology if the price is low enough.
Ordinary market economics dictate that price has a marked influence on
demand. The volume of people taking intercontinental flights or package
holidays abroad increases as air ticket prices fall; the number of car
owners rises as prices fall within the reach of the average pocket.
But the idea that the market for personal computers will explode when the
price falls to, say, Pounds 500, puts the most powerful business machines
ever invented in the same category as expensive electronic consumer products
like hi-fi sound systems or high-definition television.
Large organisations purchasing hundreds, perhaps thousands, of personal
computers a year are not part of this pattern, although lower PC prices do
increase their flexibility - they can buy rather than rent, drive different
kinds of bargains with their suppliers and spread information technology
more widely through their organisations.
But for smaller businesses, the price/demand syndrome suggests that PCs are
a 'nice-to-have' rather than 'have-to-have' option, unlike, say, a delivery
truck or, perhaps, a portable telephone. No one questions the need a
business has for a delivery truck. But the business benefits of PCs are by
no means so obvious.
It is common knowledge that many large organisations are dissatisfied with
their investment in information technology, including personal computers, so
perhaps it is not surprising that some of this disaffection should have
trickled down to smaller companies.
But large companies are not dissatisfied with their use of computers for
bread-and-butter purposes - word processing, accountancy and payroll. They
are chiefly disappointed by their lack of success in so-called
competitive-edge applications where technology should have given them an
advantage over their rivals.
There is no reason why a smaller organisation should not come up with a
competitive-edge application, but common sense dictates that their primary
aim in computerisation should be to drive some cost out of the business.
Clearly, many have not valued this opportunity at, say, Pounds 3,500, the
cost of a state-of-the-art system a couple of years ago. How many will value
it at today's price of Pounds 1,000 or less?
There are other interpretations. Some argue that low prices make it easier
for customers to buy more computers or more sophisticated computers, and
there is much in that. Yet in Europe suspicions linger that PCs are an
adornment rather than critical to a business.
It is hard to blame hardware manufacturers. Aircraft manufacturers have no
influence on the direction in which their products will fly any more than
hi-fi manufacturers can dictate their customers' choice of compact discs.
It is interesting, however, that IBM is ploughing some Dollars 60m into a
European media campaign designed to spread awareness of personal computing.
Software is another matter. Vast strides have been taken to make packaged
software simpler to use and more attractive, but there is much further to
go.
Business computing has been an act of faith for too long, and better
software - 'softer' software as the jargon would have it - must play a big
part in proving the benefits of the technology.
Until the advantages of computing to the small business are obvious and
unequivocal it is hard to see what basis there can be for agreement on the
'right' price for a personal computer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
