<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Jubilee extension 'under threat'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT may use the collapse of Canary Wharf as an excuse for
cancelling the Jubilee Line Tube extension, according to an administrator to
the insolvent office project in London's Docklands, Vanessa Houlder writes.
Mr Stephen Adamson, a partner at Ernst &amp; Young, who is an administrator to
the project, said yesterday: 'It does seem illogical that if you're talking
about a Pounds 1.7bn extension cost and you compare that with O&amp;Y's
contribution that that would be the reason for cancelling the whole project
. . . It seems that the collapse of Canary Wharf is being used as an
excuse.'
Olympia &amp; York, Canary Wharf's developers, had agreed to contribute Pounds
170m towards the extension.
No agreement was signed to help to fund the extension before the project
went into administration, the administrators emphasised.
Mr Adamson also indicated that the government was interested in taking
between 700,000 and 900,000 sq ft of office space in Canary Wharf for the
relocation of civil servants.
