<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Lords set limit on right to silence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEFENDANTS in fraud cases can no longer automatically use their right to
silence to avoid answering questions in civil proceedings, the House of
Lords ruled yesterday.
The judgment is likely to make it considerably easier for liquidators to
track down and recover missing funds in future fraud cases.
Giving judgment in the case of AT&amp;T Istel v Mr Arthur Tully, five law lords
ruled by 4 - 1 that a Court of Appeal decision restoring Mr Tully's right to
silence should be overturned.
Mr Tully had originally successfully challenged a High Court ruling that he
should provide details of transactions and assets to victims of his alleged
fraud.
Lord Templeman yesterday described the use of the right to silence in civil
proceedings as 'an archaic and unjustifiable survival from the past'.
'It is difficult to see any reason why in civil proceedings the privilege
against self-incrimination should be exerciseable so as to enable a litigant
to refuse relevant and even vital documents which are in his possession or
power and which speak for themselves.
'The Court of Appeal reached their decision with regret because they clearly
saw Mr Tully is seeking to exploit the privilege against self-incrimination
in order to frustrate the plaintiff's claims.'
The Crown Prosecution Service had stated that it would not seek to use any
information given by Mr Tully to other parties in civil proceedings.
'There is no reason why the privilege should be blatantly exploited to
deprive the plaintiffs of their civil rights and remedies if the privilege
is not necessary to protect Mr Tully,' Lord Templeman continued.
Although not directly applicable to the work of commons committees, the
ruling may ease the task of the Commons' social security committee in its
future investigations into the disappearance of the Maxwell pension funds.
The committee is likely to interview some of those who held key roles in the
Maxwell organisation, including Mr Michael Stoney, the former finance
director of Mirror Group Newspapers, and Mr Robert Bunn, the former finance
director of the Maxwell private companies.
</TEXT>
