<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Boycott threat to finance watchdog: Life companies demand
uniform stance by new SRO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE insurance companies are threatening to boycott a proposed
self-regulatory body for retail financial services unless all other
organisations that sell the products, such as banks and building societies,
are also forced to join.
The life companies argue that unless there is uniform regulation of the sale
of all retail financial products - such as life insurance, unit trusts and
personal pensions bought by individuals - some distributors will have
advantages over others and consumers will suffer.
The proposed regulator, the Private Investment Authority, is unlikely to
succeed unless the leading life insurers agree to join it and support it
financially. If regulators cannot find a suitable structure to regulate
retail financial services, the government may have to review aspects of the
Financial Services Act.
Under the act, all financial service providers must belong to a
self-regulatory organisation, but have the right to choose which one. They
also have the option of being directly regulated by the Securities and
Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog.
While life insurance companies belong to Lautro, the self-regulatory body
for the insurance and unit trust industries, the independent advisory arms
of building societies are regulated by SIB. The financial services arms of
banks are typically members of Imro, the self-regulatory body for the fund
management industry.
The membership rules and fees of all three vary.
The new authority was proposed by Sir Kenneth Clucas, a former senior civil
servant who was commissioned by SIB to review the regulatory structure for
retail financial services.
Fimbra, the regulator for independent financial intermediaries, is not
considered financially viable because its members, often small or one-person
businesses, lack the resources to make substantial contributions. In
1991-92, life companies will have to pay Pounds 14m towards the Investors
Compensation Scheme which should have been paid by Fimbra members.
Hence Sir Kenneth proposed merging Fimbra with Lautro to form the Private
Investment Authority. He also suggested that the large financial
intermediaries, about a third of Imro's members, should join the proposed
authority.
The insurance companies say they want SIB to encourage banks and building
societies to join the new authority by refusing to regulate any firm
directly unless it has been refused membership of another self-regulatory
body. They are also urging an increase in SIB membership fees.
Mr Keith Bedell-Pearce, chief executive of Prudential Financial Services,
said: 'We support the formation of the PIA but we regard it as absolutely
essential that it covers all the financial services covered by the Financial
Services Act.'
Privately the SIB is reluctant to coerce companies to join any particular
self-regulatory body because they have the right of choice and because a
regulator with a reluctant membership is unlikely to work well.
</TEXT>
