FT  21 JUL 92 / Waldegrave outlines Charter's role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Citizen's Charter amounts to a reinvention of the role of government, Mr
William Waldegrave, minister for public service, said yesterday.
Mr Waldegrave, speaking to the Institute of Directors, re-asserted the
government's commitment to privatising services still performed by the
public sector. He also highlighted the need to devise mechanisms to bring a
substitute for competition into public services where privatisation was not
possible. 'We have had to restore the principle that the government's job is
to govern, not to administer; to steer, not to row,' he said.
Where services did still have to be provided by the state, management
improvements in Whitehall should include delegating financial responsibility
and establishing clear purchaser-provider relationships.
Mr Waldegrave rejected the claim from some MPs that the establishment of
Next Steps agencies, in which parts of the Civil Service were turned into
executive bodies, diluted public accountability. Such moves improved
existing accountability, he argued, by providing a counterweight to the
centralisation of power in 'a pull downwards and outwards - to the local
provider, the user and the local community'.
However, the initiative was attacked last night by Lord Scarman, the former
law lord. He said the charter would be ineffective without legal rights -
including freedom of information and rights of redress in the courts.
Although charters could be valuable in improving public services such as
transport, health, water and gas, without the protection of a written
constitution they would not be enough to ensure higher standards.
Lord Scarman also called for a convention to draw up such a constitution,
and announced that Charter 88, the pressure group for constitutional reform,
would establish a 'citizen's inquiry'.
Mixed blessings, Page 15
</TEXT>
