<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Groggy pound hauled back from the brink: Peter Marsh says
talk of sterling devaluation will not end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BIG battalions of the world's central banks yesterday helped pull the
pound back from the brink. Even so, the worries over sterling may not yet be
over.
After scares about a possible sterling devaluation, the pound was looking
groggy before concerted intervention on foreign exchange markets succeeded
in lifting the currency.
It closed last night in London against the D-Mark at DM2.8425, nearly 1 1/2
pfennigs up on the day's low of DM2.8282. That level, reached about
lunchtime, represented the pound's lowest value against the German currency
since Britain joined the European exchange rate mechanism in October 1990.
The thrust of yesterday's operation - involving leading north American and
European central banks, including the Bank of England - was to sell D-Marks
for dollars.
The action was designed primarily to prevent the US currency from sliding to
its all-time low against the D-Mark. The German currency has gained strength
in recent weeks, particularly after last Thursday's tightening in interest
rates by the Bundesbank.
Allowing the D-Mark to continue its appreciation against the dollar, a move
exacerbated by recent interest rate cuts in the US and concern about the
faltering US economy, was in few countries' interests.
In the past week, the rampant German currency has led to serious strains in
the ERM. It has caused Italy, Belgium and the Netherlands to increase their
borrowing rates.
The strong D-Mark also threatened rises in interest rates in other European
nations, Britain included  just when they want to make borrowing cheaper to
stimulate their flagging economies. Meanwhile, the weak dollar has also
provoked concern on Wall Street.
Hence yesterday's move by the central banks - led by the US Federal Reserve
and the Bundesbank, and the first concerted intervention on such a scale
since last July - came as little surprise.
The immediate effect was to lift the dollar from DM1.447 before the action
to a close last night in Europe of DM1.4815. As pressure on all other ERM
currencies eased as a result of the weaker D-Mark, the pound firmed.
Doubts remain that sterling is out of the woods. The last time it suffered
similar fragility was in January, just after an earlier round of
interest-rate tightening by the Bundesbank to reduce German inflation
stimulated by unification.
Then, the pound fought its way out of the doldrums. It was helped by strong
statements from government ministers that devaluation was not on the agenda.
That convinced the markets that - at the levels seen in January, of about
DM2.83 or roughly 5 pfennigs above the pound's ERM floor of DM2.78 - the
pound looked cheap and was a good buy.
Six months on, the outlook has worsened. First, the UK recession has lasted
longer than expected. That has increased pressure on Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, to bring down base rates from 10 per cent - almost impossible
given the pound's position as the weakest ERM currency.
Second, the prospects for an imminent reduction in German borrowing rates
look far from propitious. Indeed, many commentators expect the Bundesbank to
follow up last week's 0.75 per cent increase in the discount rate - which
mainly affects domestic bank borrowing - with a rise later this year in its
more internationally important Lombard rate, now at 9.75 per cent.
Third, while German short-term rates have moved up, US rates have come down,
increasing the attractiveness to the international investor of the D-Mark
and exacerbating ERM strains.
Finally, there have been increasing doubts - barely evident in January  -
about whether the Maastricht agreement on European economic and monetary
union will unravel. Many investors see Emu and the ERM as linked. If
Maastricht comes finally unstuck, perhaps after a large number of 'no' votes
in the French referendum in September, then the faith of investors in the
ERM as a vehicle for pegging Europe's currencies may be weakened.
Those points explain why talk of a sterling devaluation - perhaps in the
context of an ERM-wide realignment that increases the value of the D-Mark
against the other currencies - is being taken much more seriously in the
markets than in January. It may be a long, hot summer for sterling.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
