<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Money supply figures indicate weak demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEEBLE June growth figures for money supply yesterday added to evidence that
underlying demand is still weak.
The figures from the Bank of England showed that narrow money, or M0, which
comprises mostly notes and coins in circulation, fell 0.8 per cent last
month, which is the sharpest monthly drop since late 1981.
The fall brought the year-on-year rate of growth of M0 - a good indication
of underlying consumer demand - to 1.3 per cent on a seasonally adjusted
basis, compared with 2.5 per cent in May. Broad money - M4 - rose 0.1 per
cent on the month, leaving the year-on-year rate unchanged at 5.2 per cent.
Figures for lending by banks and building societies were slightly more
encouraging. They showed that lending to the private and corporate sectors -
M4 lending - continued to grow, but only sluggishly.
Lending increased by Pounds 2.5bn last month on a seasonally adjusted basis
compared with earlier estimates of Pounds 2.3bn growth and actual average
growth of Pounds 2.2bn over the previous six months.
Mr Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, said: 'Neither broad
money nor credit indicate that the economy is moving downwards again . . .
rather the monetary indicators suggest economic stagnation, and that only a
very slow recovery in growth is in prospect during the rest of this year.'
The Bank's figures were backed up by the British Bankers' Association, the
trade body for Britain's nine biggest banking groups. The association's
figures showed that lending by its members to the private sector grew by
Pounds 1.3bn last month.
Although that was lower than the rises in April and May - Pounds 2.6bn and
Pounds 2.2bn respectively - it was the third consecutive monthly rise.
Lord Inchyra, secretary-general of the association, said: 'If one looks at
longer-term trends there does seem to be some recovery in bank lending from
the low point in March. It is, however, very patchy.'
The association's figures also showed that lending for house purchases
continued to grow modestly but that the consumer credit market remained
inert. Lending for mortgages rose by Pounds 837m last month, compared with
Pounds 596m in March, while lending to consumers rose by Pounds 189m
compared with Pounds 374m in June last year.
Consumer confidence continued to fall during the first two weeks of this
month, according to a survey by Gallup, the market research company.
A total of 31 per cent of the respondents said that they thought the general
economic situation in the country would worsen against 30 per cent who
thought it would improve.
The minus 1 per cent balance of pessimists was the lowest since February
this year, when it was minus 4 per cent. The latest figure compares with
plus 13 per cent only last month.
The survey showed that 70 per cent of respondents expect unemployment to
increase over the next 12 months against only 12 per cent who expect it to
come down.
Those who expect that their household's financial situation will improve
over the next 12 months - 23 per cent - are equally matched by those who
expect it to worsen.
</TEXT>
