<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Court in the video act
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British court system took a step into the technological age yesterday
with the launch of a video designed for jurors.
Topics covered include eligibility for jury service, what happens in court,
and a juror's legal responsibilities including turning up on time and not
discussing the case except with other jurors.
The video - a still from which is shown - was commissioned by the Lord
Chancellor's Department and will be shown to everyone called up for jury
service in England and Wales. It will partly replace the traditional
explanatory talk from the court staff, although they will still be available
to answer questions. Televisions and videos have been installed to show the
video at 45 crown courts.
Jurors are warned that they may spend some time waiting during legal
arguments, and that it is not always possible to predict the length of
trials. Mr John Taylor, parliamentary secretary to the department, said the
new televisions should be available for jurors to watch when not on a case
while the video suggests they should bring along books, crosswords or
knitting.
The video had been tried out at a number of courts around the country and
met with positive reaction, Mr Taylor said. Staff from Wood Green crown
court, north London, where the video was filmed, play all the roles, except
those of the judge, barristers and witness, who are played by actors.
</TEXT>
