<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / London's extra funding outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN REDWOOD, the local-government minister, yesterday spelt out the
scale of funds allocated to London by central government, with figures
showing that inner London authorities receive nearly Pounds 900 more for
each adult than country regions.
In outer London, the amount from grants and business rates was about Pounds
300 extra.
The figures - presented to a conference on Europe organised by
local-authority associations - will be used by ministers to defend the
government's plans to introduce a property-based tax in April next year.
London Tories are concerned that the council tax will sharply reduce the
proportion of total government grants to the south-east.
In the current year, the government allocated local authorities more than
Pounds 700 for every adult outside London and other big cities compared with
Pounds 1,000 in outer London and Pounds 1,600 in inner London.
Under the property-based local tax, councils in London and the south-east
will be expected to raise more than if poll tax had continued, because of
the large number of relatively expensive homes in the area. The amount
authorities are expected to raise from poll tax reflects broadly the number
of adults in their areas.
Although final figures are not available, one recent estimate put the shift
in grants away from London at about Pounds 300m.
Mr Redwood's figures also highlighted the difficulties the government may
face in the south-east, outside London. Shires in the north, the north-west
and the Yorkshire and Humberside region all receive at least Pounds 100 a
head more than the southern shires, which are likely to see a fall in their
proportion of government-allocated money.
When the council tax legislation went through parliament, some Tory MPs
expressed fears that the south-east would lose out through the change.
