<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Clinton's campaign at new high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHEERING crowds and buoyant polls are carrying Governor Bill Clinton's
campaign to new highs after the Democratic convention last week sealed his
nomination as the party's presidential candidate.
Convention euphoria lifted him in the opinion polls, as expected, and the
withdrawal of Mr Ross Perot appears to have further widened his lead over
President George Bush.
Accompanied by Senator Al Gore, his vice-presidential running-mate, he drew
8,000 supporters yesterday to a rally at Columbus, Ohio, the latest stop in
his 1,000-mile bus tour of eight states in the US heartland.
A Gallup poll, published yesterday by CNN and USA Today, showed Mr Clinton
as the choice of 56 per cent of those questioned, compared with 34 per cent
for Mr Bush.
It also showed Mr Clinton ahead by 20 percentage points in the south and
mid-west, and by 36 points in the north-east. In the west, he led by 13
points.
Clinton campaign officials recognise this advantage will fade. The question
is - how much of it will last, and for how long? Political analysts such as
Mr Charles Cook warn that the euphoria could lead the campaign into wasting
resources on states which might appear winnable now but in which it will
have no real chance in November, as happened to Mr Michael Dukakis in
Florida in 1988.
Texas will offer the hardest choice for the Democrats, Mr Cook warns, as
many believe Mr Perot's withdrawal places the state firmly within the
Republican president's grasp.
Feature, page 14.
</TEXT>
