<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Political patronage remains Sicilian Mafia's trump card:
Robert Graham in Rome explains why Italy's post-war battle against organised
crime has failed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE killing of Mr Paolo Borsellino, the leading anti-Mafia magistrate, on
Sunday, highlights two fundamental failings in the state's post-war campaign
against organised crime in Sicily and southern Italy - lack of co-ordination
and the inability to clean up the links between politicians and the Mafia.
Italy deploys over 250,000 carabinieri, police and financial police
throughout the country with a high proportion in the south, and overall the
country has the highest per capita ratio in uniform in the EC.
But the different forces are beset by rivalries and lack central
co-ordination of information and investigation. These jealousies and
rivalries have delayed the introduction of a new central co-ordinating
force, modelled on the American FBI, agreed last October.
There have been delays also in the introduction of a 'super-magistrate',
with special assistants in 26 regional offices, to co-ordinate the judicial
side of anti-Mafia investigation at a national level.
Magistrates have been locked in a heated controversy with the interior
ministry for six months over fears that such a move would place too much
power in the hands of politicians over the control of appointments. This
controversy held back the appointment of Mr Giovanni Falcone - the
anti-Mafia magistrate murdered in May - to the job for which the unfortunate
Mr Borsellino then became next in line.
Legislation has to pass through so many hurdles causing enormous delays in
implementation. A set of laws designed to bolster measures to fight
racketeering and extortion, one of the most pervasive aspects of organised
crime, only became operative in June, nearly nine months after being
approved by the cabinet.
It is also a question of making laws work. Since 1982 no fewer than 113 laws
and decrees have been issued to combat organised crime. But laws designed to
counter money laundering have been enmeshed in disputes between the Treasury
and the Interior Ministry; while the use of super-grass testimony -
pioneered by Mr Falcone, and the most successful means of convicting the
bosses, has yet to be properly defined and adequate protection given to
those wishing to turn evidence.
The judiciary itself is divided. While the vast majority are honest and
dedicated, organised crime has the resources to suborn and intimidate.
Recently a prominent clerk of the court in Rome processing all the sensitive
Mafia files was discovered to have been in the Mafia's pay, deliberately
ensuring key papers were lost or arrived late so that known criminals were
released from bail.
More disturbing is the capacity to intimidate demonstrated by the Falcone
and Borsellino killings, and a string of earlier murders. After the Falcone
assassination in May it was discovered that the court of Caltanissetta, due
to investigate his death, lacked the requisite magistrates because too few
wished to serve in such an exposed place. Volunteers had to be hastily
drafted in.
But the Sicilian Mafia's trump card continues to be the complicity it enjoys
with important elements of society, notably the politicians.
The issue of corrupt municipal administration is a national problem, but its
infiltration by organised crime is a phenomenon of southern Italy which
accounts for the majority of the 26 councils forcibly dissolved for abuse of
office by the interior ministry in the past nine months.
The Christian Democrats and Socialists bear a major part of the blame. They
have sustained their dominating presence through patronage of public works
contracts and sizeable development projects. It is no accident that 75 per
cent of all contracts in Sicily are awarded by private tender. This element
of patronage also explains in good measure the manner in which these two
parties retained their vote in the April general elections in the south but
lost on average 15 points of their vote in the north.
A major figure in this shadowy world was Mr Salvatore Lima, the Christian
Democrat Euro-deputy and the most powerful politician in Sicily, who was
murdered for as yet unspecified motives at the beginning of the general
election campaign in March. The party has observed total silence on his
killing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12103</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / EC seeks to expel Serbs from UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community decided yesterday to push for the expulsion of the
rump Yugoslavia from the United Nations and all other world bodies after
renewed fighting forced the suspension of relief flights to Sarajevo.
EC foreign ministers also appealed to the warring parties in Bosnia to
comply at once with the July 17 ceasefire negotiated by Lord Carrington,
whose EC peace conference, they suggested, should be broadened to involve
the UN and neighbouring countries.
But, as the fighting worsened again in Bosnia, EC ministers were clearly
unable to bring much new pressure to bear on Serbia as the chief malefactor
in the Balkan civil war.
'The news from Sarajevo, and the rest of Bosnia, is bad,' said Mr Douglas
Hurd, foreign secretary of the UK which holds the EC presidency. 'However,
we cannot allow disappointment to deter us, or to make us give up,' he
added.
The joint Serb-Montenegrin state could not be allowed to sit as 'Yugoslavia'
in the UN or other world bodies, Mr Hurd said. In a statement, EC ministers
said they would make 'early arrangements' to exert pressure in the UN to
shut Serbia out. The EC's legal view has long been that Serbia and
Montenegro should be denied the status of sole successor to the old
Yugoslavia.
But Mr Hurd said yesterday it was the first time this view had been formally
endorsed by ministers. Some ministers, notably Mr Klaus Kinkel of Germany,
would have preferred a more forthright statement that Serbia should be
expelled from the UN. By contrast, Mr Hurd said that Serb-Montenegrin
federation would be free to join the UN like any other new entity, though he
made clear this would be unlikely under present circumstances.
EC ministers pledged themselves ready to cut through Community red tape to
speed the delivery of Ecu120m (Pounds 85m) worth of promised humanitarian
aid. They also promised, in the light of the July 29 UN conference on
refugees, to 'consider urgently an equitable solution to the problems caused
by the potential inflow of refugees into neighbouring countries'.
But they failed to endorse specifically a request by Mr Kinkel, who said his
country had already taken in 100,000 refugees from Yugoslavia, to establish
a quota system to share the refugee in-take among all EC states.
Canadian General Lewis Mackenzie, the commander of UN forces in Sarajevo,
said yesterday that aid flights would only be resumed when the airport was
made safe. The UN had hoped to bring in 22 flights, carrying food and
medical supplies to the 380,000 people trapped in Sarajevo.
At least five people were reported killed and 14 wounded in a grenade attack
on the city centre yesterday. There was also heavy fighting in the eastern
Bosnian town of Gorazde.
</TEXT>
