<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Falling share markets ignore DM intervention: Bundesbank and
Fed lead selling - Government acts to head off home loans rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Economics and Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONCERTED intervention by the world's leading central banks to restrain the
soaring D-Mark and pave the way for lower interest rates failed yesterday to
prevent share prices in Europe suffering their largest fall for 11 months.
In their biggest co-ordinated action since July last year, the central
banks, led by the German Bundesbank and the US Federal Reserve, bought
dollars for D-Marks. Their action was both an effort to reduce strains in
the European exchange rate mechanism, caused by the German currency's recent
strong rise, and to halt the slide in the dollar.
While the intervention led to a sharp fall in the value of the D-Mark
against the dollar, it failed to convince stock market investors that
pressures within the ERM would be eased, opening the way for lower European
interest rates.
The intervention, in three separate waves yesterday afternoon in Europe and
New York, halted the rapid slide in the dollar which had been approaching
its record low of DM1.443 set in February 1991.
The Eurotrack index, which monitors the main European bourses, was 3 per
cent down at 1,064.04, the biggest one-day fall since August 1991 on the day
of the Moscow coup. Stock markets in London, New York and Tokyo all saw
large declines.
Yesterday's central bank intervention came against the background of
widespread gloom about the global economy, triggered by last week's increase
in the German discount rate.
That in turn has sparked fears that the Bundesbank may lift its key Lombard
interest rate, an event that would make it practically impossible for
European borrowing costs to come down without a broad ERM alignment to
revalue the D-Mark upwards.
The sombre mood was shared by investors worldwide:
In London, the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares closed down 28.2 at
2,403.7, after coming back from a 65-point loss before the central bank
intervention. Investors had earlier been unsettled about news of continuing
fragility in the UK economy, shown up by weak money supply figures.
In Italy, the stock market fell by nearly 6 per cent, partly due to
political worries sparked by the weekend killing of an anti-Mafia judge. The
Italian lira came under renewed pressure, falling close to its ERM floor
against the D-Mark, amid continued fears about the impact of higher European
interest rates.
The DAX index at the Frankfurt bourse ended 52.99 lower at 1,649.67. Both
Paris and Amsterdam saw declines of nearly 2 per cent.
On Wall Street, the Dow Jones Industrial Average recovered from an early
47-point loss to end down 28.64 at 3,303.00.
In Tokyo, before the start of European trading, the Nikkei stock index had
suffered a 4 per cent fall to close at 15,884.48. However, in the first
half-hour of trading today it had recovered by more than 150 points.
Yesterday's intervention by the central banks also involved the Bank of
England and the central banks of France, Italy, Spain, Sweden and Denmark.
In late New York trading last night, the dollar was quoted at DM1.4940, up
almost five pfennigs from its low of DM1.447 in London, where it ended the
day at DM1.4815.
But the weaker D-Mark failed to prevent sterling remaining in the doldrums.
In New York last night it was down slightly on the day at DM2.8469, after
dipping at one point in early European trading to DM2.8282, its lowest level
against the D-Mark since Britain joined the exchange rate mechanism in
October 1990.
New York traders said that the intervention worked well because markets had
not expected it.
Mr Joe Taylor, analyst with Technical Data in Boston, said: 'The market was
caught wrong-footed. Until the Fed acted, the fall (in the dollar) had been
orderly.'
However, markets believed that the dollar might drop still lower, as
analysts argued that the fundamental factors driving the dollar down were
still in play.
These include the large differential between German and US short-term
interest rates, and fears about the scale of the US economic recovery.
