<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Treasury cuts savings bond rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, IVO DAWNAY, DAVID BARCHARD and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT acted last night to head off a widespread rise in the cost of
home loans by cutting the interest rate offered on its highly successful new
National Savings product, the First Option Bond.
The move follows an aggressive campaign by building societies, which have
been complaining that the bond has been syphoning off their deposits.
The gross interest rate paid on the bond has been reduced from 10.34 per
cent to 9.67 per cent in a move described by a National Savings official as
'highly unusual'.
Mr Andrew Longhurst, chief executive of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester - the
society which raised its rates in response to the bond - said: 'It is good
news and we are delighted. We need to get into the office tomorrow to look
at the effect of the reduction . . . before we make a cut in our mortgage
rate,' he said.
At Leeds Permanent, Mr Mike Blackburn, chief executive, said he was
impressed with the government's speed of movement. 'It looks as though they
are committed to seeing a lower interest rate', he said.
The Woolwich welcomed the Treasury move, saying it made a mortgage rate
increase 'most unlikely'.
Mr Longhurst also disclosed that he met Treasury ministers on Friday to
explain why his society, the sixth biggest, had increased its mortgage rate
that day. 'They were understanding and sympathetic.'
Building societies had said that to retain their deposits they were being
forced they were being forced to raise savings rates, which put them under
pressure to lift mortgage rates as well.
The threat of a widespread mortgage rate rise, which would lead to further
delays in recovery of the housing market and the economy, has contributed to
sharp falls in share prices.
National Savings said that sales of the bond in the first two weeks had been
higher than expected. The First (or fixed interest rate savings tax-paid)
bond, which carried a net interest rate of 7.75 per cent, attracted Pounds
112m during the nine days since becoming available on July 7, a large amount
for a new savings product.
Only once before, in 1984, has National Savings taken steps to reduce sales
of one of its products. In that case, it withdrew a new issue after just
five weeks.
Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, said: 'It is now
clear that the new bond will remain attractive and meet the government's
needs (to help finance its borrowing requirement) with a lower interest
rate.'
The rate on the First Option Bond will be reduced from noon today. Those who
have sent an application by post will only benefit if the form arrives
before then. National Savings ran a big publicity campaign at the weekend to
sell the bond.
Woolwich tax battle, Page 6
Background, Page 7
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
