<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Capital Markets: Doubts mar launch of Japanese
securities watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Tokyo stock market's first official securities watchdog began work
yesterday, amid doubts that it would succeed in restoring investor
confidence in the market.
Mr Toshihiro Mizuhara, chairman of Japan's version of the US Securities and
Exchange Commission, said the body's mission was to create a market that can
deserve the trust of investors.
But market participants remain sceptical of the commission's effectiveness
because of its closeness to the finance ministry - which appoints its
members - and its small staff. The commission has around 200 members
compared with the 2,900 at the SEC.
Mr Kiyoshi Nikami, chief researcher at Japan Securities Research Institute,
said the new commission lacked resources and independence, and would have to
rely on the ministry for its operations.
The ministry yesterday said it would reduce the number of official notices
and oral guidance of its securities bureau to make its administration more
transparent.
The move follows criticism that the ministry's securities administration,
based on unclear oral guidance, had been one of the causes behind last
year's securities scandals.
</TEXT>
