FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Renault to sell control of
loss-making Argentine unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RENAULT, the French government-owned car maker, plans to transfer control of
its loss-making Argentine subsidiary to three Argentine and Brazilian
investors.
Renault says it has signed a letter of intent with a group of investors led
by Mr Manuel Antelo, head of a leading Argentine components maker, who will
together own 67 per cent of COFAL, a Luxembourg-based vehicle created to
hold Renault's former 72 per cent stake in the subsidiary.
Renault will still hold 33 per cent of COFAL, cutting its share in the
subsidiary to 24 per cent. The remaining shares are held by the public.
Renault would not disclose a sale price or indicate how the buyers were
financing their acquisition.
However, Renault is listed on the Buenos Aires stock exchange where it has a
market capitalisation of Dollars 841.5m, valuing the sale at about Dollars
408m.
Renault's retreat is taking place against a background of increasing
competition, government demands for greater investment and economic
integration with Brazil.
