FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Samsung in China VCR move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SAMSUNG Electronics of South Korea plans to establish a 50/50 joint venture
factory in Tianjin, China to produce video cassette recorder (VCR) machines
and components.
Samsung's joint venture with Tianjin Telecommunications and Broadcasting is
the single largest corporate investment by a South Korean company in China.
The two companies will invest Dollars 60m in the joint venture, Tianjin
Samsung Electronics, which is expected to produce 600,000 VCRs by 1997 with
an annual turnover of Dollars 200m.
The South Korean government recently decided to build an industrial park in
Tianjin for small Korean companies involved in such labour-intensive
industries as textiles and electronics. China is attractive as a source of
cheap labour.
The Samsung move is the first big investment to be concluded since China
signed an investment guarantee agreement with South Korea in early May.
South Korean investment in China has been insignificant until this year when
it suddenly became the most popular area of foreign investment by Korean
companies.
Korean investment in China amounted to Dollars 84.9m during the first half
of 1992, a fivefold increase against a year ago.
Korean investment is likely to increase rapidly once the two countries
establish diplomatic relations, possibly this year or next.
</TEXT>
