<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Schering divisions acquired by
Witco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE COLITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SCHERING, the German pharmaceuticals and chemicals group, is selling its
industrial and organic chemicals operations to Witco, a US chemicals
company, for DM660m (Dollars 410m).
The Berlin-based group said the disposal, which is to take effect in the
autumn, marked the first important step towards concentrating on its core
businesses of drugs and agricultural chemicals.
The sale was a blow to the VIAG group of Germany, which had bid to acquire
the two units.
William R. Toller, Witco chairman, said the acquisition would double the
group's international business. Witco had sales last year of DM2.6bn. The
group, which has European subsidiaries in the UK, France and the
Netherlands, is an important producer of plastic additives and
oleo-chemicals, in addition to oil products and construction materials.
Schering was also considering bids from a number of companies for its
electro-plating activities, which last year had sales of DM329m. It expects
to announce a deal shortly.
Schering's industrial chemicals turnover last year was DM454m, with total
group sales at DM6.3bn. However, industrial chemicals sales fell 1 per cent
compared with advances of 15 per cent for pharmaceuticals and 8 per cent for
agricultural chemicals. Turnover in organic chemicals was DM440m, up 8 per
cent.
Apart from smaller organic chemicals subsidiaries in the UK, Spain and the
US, most of Schering's industrial and organic chemicals output is
concentrated in Germany.
The Treuhand privatisation agency said Samsung, the South Korean
conglomerate, had not yet acquired Werk fur Fernsehelektronik (WF) in east
Berlin for Dollars 20m. It said no contract had been signed, although
negotiations had reached a final stage.
</TEXT>
