<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / International Company News: Philips to reduce working
capital and sell property
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PHILIPS, the Dutch electronics group whose share price has fallen by nearly
a third over the past four weeks, is planning to reduce working capital and
the size of its property portfolio by 'several billions of guilders' in a
multi-year effort to cut borrowings.
The company said that more efficient management of group assets would 'have
a positive impact on profits, interest cover, utilisation of tax losses and
the debt/equity ratio'.
According to an article in the company's in-house magazine, the decision was
taken at a recent meeting between senior managers and the group management
committee headed by Mr Jan Timmer, president. It described the move as a new
phase in Mr Timmer's two-year campaign to turn round the fortunes of the
Netherlands' premier industrial company.
The lowering of working capital is to be achieved over the 'next few years'
by reducing the amount of money invested in inventories and receivables,
which last year totalled about Fl 25bn (Dollars 15bn).
Philips also said that the 45,000 jobs cuts of the past two years had led to
opportunities for reviewing its property and building portfolio. However,
the sale of property would probably take longer than the reduction of
working capital because of the malaise in the property market.
Philips noted that each 1 per cent cut in inventories and receivables would
generate Fl 250m in cash and reduce annual interest payments by Fl 25m. The
company had liabilities of Fl 16.9bn in 1991.
Philips' share price has plunged to around Fl 26 from Fl 38 on June 17, when
the company warned that the depressed state of the global consumer
electronics market would cause a substantial decline in second-quarter
results. The downturn was accelerated last week following the news that a
top executive in consumer electronics, Mr Gaston Bastiaens, was leaving to
join Apple Computer.
</TEXT>
