<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / UK Company News: Dividends the only light in property gloom
 -As share prices hit a new low Christopher Price considers a depressed
market sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A sector used to depressing developments, the news that property shares
had hit a new low relative to the FT-A All Share index was greeted with a
benign shrug by most industry observers.
'The sector's still got some downside left,' said Mr John Atkins, property
analyst at stockbroker UBS Phillips &amp; Drew. 'It's a question of confidence
and we see little good news coming out to bring buyers back into the sector
in the short-term.'
Mr Graham Stanley at County NatWest agreed: 'Every time in the last four
years that it's looked like the sector's hit the bottom and it's the right
time to buy, it's actually been better to sell.'
Property shares have mirrored the dramatic decline in property prices during
the last four years, underpinned by a welter of statistics which have
charted the sector's spiral decline.
Since their peak of November 1988, property shares have underperformed the
market by 64 per cent - including a slide of 25 per cent this year alone.
Companies have been hit by declining net asset values and falling rents,
particularly in the commercial market, where an oversupplied market has been
made worse as offices have been vacated by recession-hit companies.
According to the index prepared by Richard Ellis, the surveyors, rental
values fell 16 per cent in the year to end-June 1992, including a drop of
nearly 3 per cent during the last month, the biggest single monthly fall
since 1978, when the index began.
Recent gloom on receding hopes of a cut in interest rates has been deepened
by the continuing effects of the recession. They have prompted growing fears
that dividends could be at risk, particularly in companies with heavy
exposure to the wilting office market.
With asset values crumbling investors have become wary about using a
company's own valuation of its assets as a judge of the company's worth.
They have focused on the dividend yield, which, when a company has a high
proportion of long-term office contracts, such as MEPC and Slough Estates,
has been largely guaranteed.
But even that aspect is being undermined by the length of the present slump.
Rental income is looking less secure as a growing number of tenants go out
of business. With dividend yield now suspect, investor confidence has again
been shaken and share prices further undermined.
Mr Stanley said the problem could recede, providing recovery came within the
next 12 months.
'While dividend worries are largely behind the current weakness in some
stocks, we think that most companies will hold theirs. And if we do start to
get some recovery at the start of next year then investors' confidence in
asset valuation will gradually increase and so will the confidence
underpinning the share prices.'
However, he warned that dividends would then be more likely to be cut as
maintained payments would no longer be needed to retain confidence.
Institutions looking at property companies for security and outperformance
of the market are having to search very hard.
Both County NatWest and UBS forecast that the sector will again underperform
the market this year.
However, they add that selected stocks have declined to such a level that
they may prove irresistible to investors.
For these reasons County likes Land Securities. UBS, which is advising
'underweight' clients to start rebuilding their property portfolios, is
backing MEPC and Slough Estates. Both tip British Land.
In spite of such recommendations, even bargain hunters are still staying
away. 'Business has never been so quiet,' said one trader. 'There are too
many people with burnt fingers to trust this sector again in a hurry.'
The lack of buyer interest has prompted one big broking firm to bid down
existing quoted prices during the past two weeks in an attempt to find a
level at which buyers will come out.
However, such is the fragile state of the sector that the move inspired a
fresh bout of dividend concern and a further plunge in prices.
'It's a very dangerous game to play given the nervous state of the market.'
said Mr Atkins. 'But of course it would be different if we could say values
will recover over the next year, but we can't.
'What we do know is that before then, several more companies will go into
liquidation and others will report worsening losses.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
