<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / UK Company News: Electron reaps restructuring benefits with
rise to Pounds 1.42m
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
RESTRUCTURING at Electron House, begun two years ago, is working through in
results with the electronic components, computer systems and services
distributor benefiting from reduced costs and lower working capital.
A proposed sale of the wholesale computing business operations of Bytech
Computers for some Pounds 5m will effectively reduce borrowings by Pounds
9m, and cut the ratio of debt to shareholders' funds from 110 per cent to 25
per cent.
The business was being acquired by its senior management team led by 3i, the
investment capital group.
Sales within the group will be almost halved but it will be able to
concentrate resources on higher margin business.
Pre-tax profit rose 47 per cent to Pounds 1.42m in the year to May 31,
against Pounds 968,000. Turnover slipped to Pounds 125.4m (Pounds 126.9m),
to which the operations being sold contributed Pounds 61m.
Mr Robert Leigh, chairman, said the Australian and New Zealand businesses
recovered to produce a 'more acceptable' performance. The UK component
companies, excluding the car aerial business from which the group withdrew
last year, increased sales and profits marginally.
Computer companies generally produced a good result although CEM lost sales
through the temporary moratorium on government spending in Northern Ireland.
Earnings were 2.62p (1.65p); the sale and subsequent reorganisation should
have little effect on earnings, Mr Leigh said. The final dividend is 1.35p
for a 2.35p (2.25p) total.
As to prospects, he told shareholders that business continued to improve
slowly through increased market share and productivity rather than the
market showing any signs of uplift.
