<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Foreign concern over Italy's health: Worldwide worry when a
state holding company defaults
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospect of one of the G7 group of leading industrialised countries
defaulting on its foreign debts is the sort of thing that makes bankers lie
awake at night.
It was not surprising, then, that a frisson of fear rippled through the
international banking community over the weekend as it was confirmed that
one of Italy's big state holding companies does not intend to repay its
debts on time.
Efim, which has debts of L8,500bn (Pounds 3.87bn), is the sick man among the
country's state-run industrial combines. Many of its subsidiaries, which
number more than 100, are tied up in defence, aluminium and other industries
which are going through a tough period.
Yesterday's publication of an official decree confirmed the group's fate. It
is to be wound up by an administrator and its assets sold off. In the
meantime, the group - regarded by foreign bankers as virtually an arm of the
Italian treasury - will not service or repay any of its debts. That
unilateral moratorium could last two years.
If, as expected, the money raised from disposals does not cover Efim's big
debts, then the administrator will issue the group's creditors with up to
L4,000bn of government-backed bonds.
The Italian authorities have tried to put a positive gloss on the demise of
one of its top tier of industrial holding companies. Successive
administrations had failed to deal with the gathering problems at Efim; at
least now the problems are being tackled.
Foreign bankers have not seen things the same way. There are believed to be
17 separate syndicates of banks involved, put together at different times to
lend about Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.03bn) to Efim and its subsidiaries.
Manufacturers Hanover (now merged with Chemical Bank) and Mitsubishi Trust
play a leading role in a number of these, though most international banks
turn up in one or more.
Part of what has set the bankers' nerves on edge was the manner in which
they learnt of Efim's fate. Neither the company nor the treasury warned
banks of their plans in advance, or made any effort to create the illusion
that they were consulting with their creditors. If this is how the
government handles the break-up of one of its largest industrial groups,
what chance is there for a smooth reorganisation of the country's state
sector?
Reduced to following events in newspapers or on newswires as news first
broke at the end of last week, one banker gave vent to his anger: 'Efim is
virtually an arm of the treasury. They frankly have to get this one right
otherwise Italy will be no better than an Argentina or a Brazil.'
The cloud of uncertainty continued to engulf bankers yesterday. 'Everyone is
trying to find out what the hell's going on. We're ringing other banks to
ask them, but when they pick up the phone, they ask us the same question,'
said one.
Other creditors worked hard to defuse what was in danger of becoming an
angry face-off between the Italian treasury and foreign bankers.
However, no banker likes to be told, without consultation, that debts are
not going to be paid on time. The manner in which Efim's demise was handled
is likely to live on in bankers' memories for some time.
Two immediate questions now trouble Efim's creditors. If the group's assets
do not cover its liabilities, how great will the shortfall be? And will the
Italian treasury's compensation arrangements make good the loss?
SG Warburg, the UK investment bank which acts as agent on a number of loans
to Efim and its subsidiaries, has been asked to value the group's assets,
along with Mediobanca, the private Italian bank.
The Italian government's pronouncements suggest that all creditors will be
repaid in full. But important questions have yet to be tackled. How will the
treasury set the interest rate on the bonds? Will the interests of all the
many different syndicates of bank creditors be taken into account, or will
some come off worse than others? Squaring the interests of all bank
creditors will not be easy.
The waves from the Efim affair are likely to be felt more widely. For a
start, Italian borrowers will find it virtually impossible to borrow from
foreign banks until the dust has settled. That much was clear yesterday as
bankers moved to freeze their exposure limits to Italy at current levels
until they can gauge the extent of the Efim problem.
Many foreign banks have only recently begun to lend again to Italy following
a row last year over the collapse of Federconsorzi, an agricultural group.
Although banks argued that the group had operated with an implicit state
guarantee, they were eventually forced to accept back only three quarters of
their claims.
Lenders to Italy's other main state holding companies are also now pawing
through the documentation behind their loans to see whether their rights are
affected. Such documents usually contain cross-default clauses, giving
lenders the right to call in their loans if the borrower defaults on any of
its other commitments.
The position is complicated by the insertion in yesterday's decree of a
clause apparently requiring bankers to renounce any claims against Efim
which arose before yesterday. 'We are getting legal advice on what it all
means,' the head of one syndicate of banks said.
The wrangle between Italy and its foreign bankers has come at an unfortunate
moment. Moody's, the US credit-rating agency, is already looking into
whether it should downgrade Italy from its current AA1 status. It already
fails to match up to the AAA standing of the other G7 countries, and any
further relegation would have a serious impact in the eyes of the
international financial community. With the debacle surrounding Efim, such a
move may just have come one step closer.
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
