<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Letter: Transport - conflicts and little hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ALI ABBAS ALI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Richard Tomkins appears to be over-enthusiastic about the benefits of
private enterprise in the early years of the railways ('Politicians send the
trains down yet another track', July 15). While the achievements of this
sector in its first 50 or so years are indeed impressive and laudable, the
means by which they were made are open to criticism. There is too much
evidence in this period of rail company managers displaying little
competitive edge and of a huge misuse of funds in over optimistic investment
and aggressive, imperfect competition for us to look forward to a future of
private railways with anything more than the faintest glimmer of hope.
Ali Abbas Ali,
St John's College,
Cambridge CB2 1TP.
