<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Letter: Transport - conflicts and little hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID STARKIE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your editorial, 'No revolution in British Rail' (July 15), concludes
that the rail white paper, by separating track infrastructure from trains,
provides an opportunity to level the playing field between road and rail. To
complete the process you advocate higher fuel taxes and tolls on motorways.
It is perhaps not widely appreciated that legislation which enables the
playing field to be levelled reached the statute book last year. This
initiative - The New Roads and Street Works Act - allows for
privately-financed tolled roads. It has had very little impact. In several
instances untolled public schemes have been chosen instead of the tolled
schemes suggested by the private sector. A concession has been granted for
one privately financed road only and even this is not certain to proceed.
The government needs to revive this flagging policy. To do this, it needs to
level another playing field by placing the department of transport's road
planners, some of whom strongly oppose toll roads, at arm's length from
those advising ministers. At the present time there is a clear conflict of
interest, especially when rival private and public schemes are seeking
approval.
David Starkie,
Garden Cottage,
Benham Park,
Newbury, Berks RG16 8LX
</TEXT>
