<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Leading Article: Expenditure priorities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ON WEDNESDAY, the British cabinet will meet to discuss its strategy for the
public spending round. It does so in inauspicious circumstances: the
government has lost its previously sound fiscal position; it has little
chance of balancing its budget in the medium term; and it will be unable to
combine its current spending plans with continued membership of the ERM and
lower taxes. In consequence, the Treasury will assail whatever looks the
least bit vulnerable, while its charter-waving opponents in the spending
ministries will put up an equally spirited defence.
The short- to medium-term worries are not imaginary. As recently as 1988-89,
the public sector's debt repayment was 3 per cent of gross domestic product.
When disinflation started to bite, however, that debt repayment turned into
a borrowing requirement likely to exceed 5 per cent of GDP in 1992-93 and
1993-94. The main reason for the slide into the red is that between 1990-91,
when the PSBR was zero, and next year the government planned to increase
public spending by 11.6 per cent in real terms. But over the same period
real gross domestic product is, barring a sudden recovery, likely to fall.
Public spending cannot grow faster than real GDP for long without parallel
increases in taxes. With the election talk of recovery revealed as
hyperbole, the government's thoughts naturally turn towards a tough spending
round. But the round should be more than just tough, it should demonstrate a
sense of priorities. Otherwise, the main outcome is likely to be the usual
wasteful cuts in public investment.
Individual responsibility
In the first year of a new parliament, a government that also starts with a
net ratio of public sector debt to GDP of only about 30 per cent need not
panic. The scale of the actual and prospective increases in the PSBR
underlines the case for a rethink of public spending. How else, after all,
can cuts be made in a rational manner? But it is not the only reason for
such a reconsideration. The question a government committed to individual
responsibility and low taxation should ask is what it should be doing in the
first place.
The questioning should start from what it does now. Total government
expenditure amounted to 42 per cent of GDP last year (excluding
privatisation proceeds). Some 29 per cent of this was for social security,
15 per cent for health and personal social services, 13 per cent for
education, 9 1/2 per cent for defence, 5 per cent for law and order and 4
per cent for transport.
These six areas accounted for three quarters of total spending. Since debt
interest added another 7 per cent, all other governmental activity amounted
to less than a fifth of the total.
Charter standards
Is it necessary for the government to provide retirement pensions to all,
independent of their individual wealth? Should state education be available
free at the point of use to every parent, independent of their means? What
about health? Is it possible to meet citizen-charter standards for these and
other services without greater funding and, if so, should more of that
funding not come from the users?
How much of the road building programme can be funded through toll roads or
financed directly through user charges? Given the inability of the Treasury
to distinguish sensibly between capital and current spending, can other
areas of capital spending be privatised or charged to users, if necessary
through earmarked taxation?
These questions are uncomfortable to ask. But any sensible programme for
long term control of public spending has to start from them. This does not
mean that there is no alternative, especially for a hard-pressed government.
It consists of cutting anything that has no huge lobby behind it,
particularly capital spending. It consists of pretending that government can
do all it now promises to do - provide first rate education and health
services, for example - without raising extra revenue. It consists, in
effect, of spreading a grey blanket of underfunding and mediocrity over the
services that are most important to the public.
Aneurin Bevan called priorities the language of socialism. It is not. It is
the language of good government. Time will soon tell whether Mr Major's
government has the nerve to try to speak it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
