<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Arts: Don Quixote - London Promenade Concerts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROBERTO Gerhard was born in Catalonia in 1896 and died in Cambridge in 1970,
having reached Britain as a Spanish Civil War exile more than three decades
earlier. These facts - and, even more important, Gerhard's marvellously
fertile, open-spirited inventiveness as a composer - were the salient ones
in the background to the revival of his 1950 ballet Don Quixote in Sunday's
Albert Hall Promenade concert by the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra.
This was an important revival - it was billed as the first British concert
performance of the complete score (as distinct from the various suites and
sets of dances extracted from it, which are often done).
In common with the Sheridan opera The Duenna, it was composed during the
first years of Gerhard's exile; and like that opera (which was belatedly
unveiled to the world in Madrid earlier this year), Don Quixote is an
exuberant and imaginative reworking of Gerhard's Iberian musical inheritance
in up-to-date 20th century terms.
The scenario of the ballet was drawn from Cervantes by Gerhard himself;
apparently it was the quirkiness of his narrative plotting, pacing and
shaping that accounted for the work's failure to take root in the ballet
repertory after the Royal Opera House premiere in 1950 (with choreography by
De Valois, decor by Burra, and Helpmann and Fonteyn in the leading roles).
In concert the dramatic pressures of the score's narrative recede in
importance behind the significance of its purely musical qualities; and in
total, these were shown by Simon Rattle and his orchestra to be abundantly
rich.
Falla's great Spanish ballets are in the background. But so is Berg - as a
Schoenberg pupil in the 1920s Gerhard's eyes and ears had long been widened
to the value and importance of all the main European musical trend. In
parallel with the opera, the special distinction of Don Quixote lies in its
attempt - heartfelt, energetic, generous and also keenly focused - to
reconcile Gerhard's artistic past, present and future.
His success, which seems to me even greater than in The Duenna, makes one
grieve all over again at the craven provincialism of the wartime and
post-wartime British musical world in its failure to embrace this born
theatre-man and draw on his gifts.
It is in the psychological depiction of Don Quixote that the modernist
Gerhard shows his greatest percipience, developing what the programme-note
writer David Drew calls a 'serial skeleton' to depict the 'world of (his)
crazed imagination'.
The sinuous blending of outer and inner worlds in a musico-dramatic context
is what lends the music its special fascination - that, and the sheer sound
of the music, which, with its piquant concertante role for the piano and its
constant dry rattle of Spanish rhythmic patterning, proves wonderfully
alluring. I should have liked to encounter it in a less reverberant, more
theatre-like acoustical ambience than that provided by the Albert Hall (as a
result of which certain transitional passages seemed to me slightly
over-extended).
But for Rattle's eloquent, warm-spirited and utterly convinced conducting of
the music, and for the lustrous playing of the CBSO, there can be only the
highest praise. In the second part of this splendid Prom, the CBSO chorus
filled the higher platform tiers and Thomas Trotter the organ loft for one
of those uniquely uplifting Rattle accounts of the Janacek Glagolitic Mass
that sends everyone out of the hall a happier and better person for having
heard it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12174</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAA7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Arts: Almeida Concerts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLEMENTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE concerts of contemporary music fitted around the three productions of
the first incarnation of Almeida Opera, at the Almeida Theatre, London N1,
have given useful breadth and variety to the season. The idea of relating
these programmes to the operas has been generally successful, and only
occasionally strained. As a template for future seasons it seems eminently
flexible.
The evening devoted to 'Musica Transalpina', tracing the Italianate
influence into northern Europe as a corollary to the production of Stephen
Oliver's Mario and the Magician, brought one important revival - a
performance by Music Projects under Richard Bernas of The Deluge, Alexander
Goehr's 1959 setting of da Vinci. It is a toughly argued, sinewy piece, with
intense vocal writing for the soprano and mezzo soloists. But 30 years on it
seems curiously fixed in its time, holding its passionate lyricism under
tight control.
The remainder of the Music Projects programme was mixed - a beautifully
idiomatic account of Schoenberg's Serenade (still though a work that never
fails to outstay its welcome), and a poised, neat version of Donatoni's
exquisite Arpege. There was a dutiful premiere of some new Michael Finnissy:
Various Nations was commissioned by Almeida Opera, yet turned out to be a
curiously perfunctory piece. A narrator (Eleanor Bron here) delivers
readings from a Victorian children's geography book, full of hilarious
colonial condescension, while the ensemble runs through a sequence of
suitably ethnic pastiches. One waits to be surprised, but the expected
musical twist or sting never happens, and the piece fizzles out tamely and
without consequence.
Sunday's closing concerts were given by the Bergen-based ensemble BIT 20.
The early-evening programme promised two British premieres, of Kaija
Saariaho's gravely beautiful Lichtbogen and Arne Nordheim's emptily
rhetorical Tre Voci. But neither was new to this country; Almeida Opera's
programme book seems to have inherited its predecessor's piratical claims to
first performances.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
