<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / People: Finance moves
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Rt Hon Tim Renton MP has become parliamentary consultant to ROBERT
FLEMING HOLDINGS.
*****
John Fenn has been appointed London representative of the BANCO ECONOMICO of
Salvador, on the retirement of Gerald Walkden.
*****
Derek Tullett has become president of TULLETT &amp; TOKYO FOREX INTERNATIONAL
GROUP and Rick Magee chairman. Mark Perkins has been appointed to the board
of Tullett &amp; Tokyo Forex (London).
*****
David Gillespie has moved from BZW to be finance director of QUILTER
GOODISON COMPANY.
*****
Allied-Lyons, the international food and drinks group, is continuing to mend
its fences with the City. Miles Rivett-Carnac, 59, a deputy chairman of
Barings, has been appointed a non-executive director.
Michael Jackaman, who took over the chairmanship of Allied-Lyons following
the Pounds 147m currency trading loss last year, says that Rivett-Carnac's
extensive international background in merchant banking and investment will
bring a valuable extra dimension to board deliberations.
Rivett-Carnac is the second non-executive to be appointed to the board since
Jackaman took the helm last year. John Robb, Wellcome's chief executive, was
appointed in October and other new non-executive faces are expected.
Jackaman says that he would like the number of executive and non-executive
directors to be roughly equal. New directors will be appointed for three
years, with the option of renewing their term for another three years.
Jackaman first met Rivett-Carnac when Barings was one of the advisers on the
group's Hiram Walker acquisition. However, he stresses that Barings is not
retained as Allied-Lyons' permanent financial adviser. Given that
Rivett-Carnac is close to retirement, Jackaman says he thinks there is no
conflict of interest in having the chairman of one of the City's bigger fund
managers on his board.
