FT  21 JUL 92 / People: A team to get Ford out of reverse
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Tony Brigden, 50, currently director of parts and service operations, has
been given the tough task of trying to reverse Ford's slumping sales
fortunes in the UK.
Brigden's is one of several new appointments Ford of Britain announced in
its restructuring of senior sales management yesterday. Once the
unchallenged market leader with a share of 30 per cent, Ford's share is now
in the low 20s and it is becoming hard-pressed to stay ahead of
second-placed Vauxhall.
Brigden is to take over from Colin Breathwick, currently fleet sales
director, who takes up the new appointment of director, retail strategy, on
August 1. Reporting directly to chairman and managing director Ian
McAllister, Breathwick, 49, will be responsible for analysing Ford's
existing approaches to the marketplace.
Brigden is to be succeeded in parts and service by Phil Cazaly, 45,
currently director of sales and service operations at Ford of Europe, based
in Germany.
Ford believes a 'cultural change' is taking place in customer attitudes
towards the car; during the 1990s car ownership will become less important
to motorists, who will be more concerned with 'simply having access' to cars
through a variety of finance or leasing schemes.
*****
Nigel Blythe-Tinker has been appointed company secretary of SUTER, in
succession to Antony Paton Walsh who is retiring early because of ill
health.
