<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / The Week in Luxembourg: ECJ upholds UK benefit rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRICK COURT CHAMBERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECJ has upheld UK state pension rules which discriminate in favour of
women. Under UK legislation, men must contribute to the state scheme for 44
years for a full pension, whereas women need only contribute for 39 years;
men have to contribute to the scheme if they are employed between the ages
of 60 and 64, whereas women do not.
The ECJ held that such discrimination was lawful as EC law permitted
exceptions to the general rule of non-discrimination in this area, but only
insofar as such exceptions were necessary in order to achieve the objectives
of EC social security legislation and only on a temporary basis. The Court
also stated that an enforced change of the national rules now would lead to
financial disequilibrium of the UK pension scheme.
Case 9/91: The Queen v secretary of state for social security ex parte the
Equal Opportunities Commission, ECJ FC, July 7 1992.
National waste provisions overturned
In a case which provoked environmental concern, Belgium was found to have
breached EC obligations by a regional Wallonian degree banning waste from
other member states.
EC legislation sets out procedures for the transhipment of hazardous waste;
the Wallonian decree went beyond these rules and was thus unlawful. However,
the ban did not breach general EC waste provisions, where states still have
residual competence. Belgium is thus in the anomalous position of being able
to ban imports of non-toxic waste, but not of toxic waste.
The Court also found that the Rome Treaty provisions on free movement of
goods applied in principle to waste. Arguments that the national provisions
were discriminatory against non-Belgian waste and thus unlawful were
rejected, the Court citing Basle Convention obligations on self-sufficiency
and proximity in waste elimination to justify the difference in treatment.
C-2/90: Commission v Belgium, ECJ FC, July 9 1992.
UK immigration law unlawful
UK immigration rules were ruled unlawful by the ECJ as conflicting with EC
provisions on free movement.
Mr Singh, an Indian national married to a British citizen, worked with his
wife in Germany for two years before returning to England. On the basis of
pending divorce proceedings between them, the UK authorities refused Mr
Singh indefinite leave to remain in the UK. He stayed beyond the time
allowed and a deportation order was made against him. He appealed, arguing
that he had a Community right to stay in the UK as the spouse of a Community
national.
Under Rome Treaty provisions, Community nationals are entitled to reside and
work anywhere within the EC. As these rights would be restricted if
obstacles to the entry and residence of their existing spouses/children were
raised by domestic provisions, the Court held the UK provisions unlawful.
C-370/90: The Queen v Immigration Appeal Tribunal and Surinder Singh, ex
parte home secretary, ECJ FC, July 7 1992.
Spanish immigration law unlawful
Spanish rules on dual nationality, whereby nationality is based on the last
habitual residence, were held to be unlawful by the ECJ insofar as they
conflicted with EC rules on establishment and the provision of services.
Mr Micheletti, a dual national of Argentina and Italy, studied at university
in Argentina and then came to Spain to work. He was refused a residence
permit on the grounds that he was an Argentine and had last been resident in
Argentina. On a reference for a preliminary ruling, the ECJ held that
although member states were allowed to set their own rules on nationality,
these rules had to respect EC law. Thus, where an individual had Community
rights because he was a Community national, these rights could not be
restricted by domestic provisions.
C-369/90: Mario Vincente Micheletti and others v Delagacion del Govierno en
Cantabria, ECJ FC, July 7 1992.
Belgian social security law upheld
The restriction of state disability allowances to Belgian nationals was
upheld by the ECJ on the grounds that it did not infringe relevant EC rules.
While living in Belgium, the Iranian wife of an Italian national tried to
claim a disability allowance from the Belgian state on the basis that as the
spouse of an EC national, she was entitled to benefits available in the
member state where she resided. The Court did not accept this argument,
stating that her rights to EC social security allowances were restricted to
those she could receive as a member of the family of an EC national. As the
spouse was seeking the allowance in her own right and not by virtue of being
the spouse of a Community national, the relevant EC rules were not
applicable.
C-243: Belgium v Noushin Taghavi, ECJ 1CH, July 8 1992.
Other cases
Italy was held in breach of its Rome Treaty obligations, having failed to
implement two directives relating to threadworm and brucellosis in due time.
C-270/91: Commission v Italy, ECJ FC, July 8 1992.
Milk quotas can lawfully be denied to farmers who have let out their land
prior to demanding their quota, as it is the tenant and not the original
farmer who has the use of the land and therefore the right to the quota.
C-236/90: Reinhard Maier v Freistaat Bayern, ECJ 3CH, July 9 1992.
A minimum level of value added tax levied on second-hand cars sold in
Belgium was found to be contrary to EC VAT provisions in that it would lead
to VAT being charged twice on the same good.
C-131/91: BV 'K' Line Air Service Europe v NV Eularts &amp; Belgium, ECJ 6CH,
July 9 1992.
A German worker who worked in the UK, paid national insurance contributions
and received unemployment benefit there, was entitled, on her return to
Germany, to unemployment benefit in Germany. The Court emphasised, however,
that such benefits could not be cumulated.
C-102: Doris Knock v Bundesanstalt fur Arbeit, ECJ 4CH, July 8 1992.
This completes the reports for this term. Judgments delivered in the
vacation will be reported later.
</TEXT>
