<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Management (The Growing Business): Private eyes need a nose
for snooping - Want to start out in a new line of business? Thomas Slemen
begins a series which offers advice on some unusual openings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By THOMAS SLEMEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anyone can become a private detective. There is no need for a licence, nor
for membership of a professional body, although a little knowledge of the
law will help. About half the private detectives in Britain are former
policemen who have either retired or left the Force early, but you do not
have to be an ex-policeman to become a competent private investigator.
The right person should be observant, persistent, have a good memory, and
possess the stamina to work unsociable hours.
They must be inconspicuous when following a subject and have a basic
knowledge of psychology to fathom a motive or persuade an interviewee to
part with secret information.
The profession of the private detective does not have an official status and
is not recognised by the police, so private investigators are not subject to
supervision and they do not have to abide by a code of practice.
There are a number of detective agencies advertised in the Yellow Pages
which may take on trainee private eyes.
After a two-year training period with an agency, the trainee can apply to
become a member of the ABI (Association of British Investigators) by taking
the ABI examination.
The other main association is the IPI (Institute of Professional
Investigators) which is based in Preston.
Both the ABI and the IPI offer thorough training and may give the
prospective detective a stamp of credibility.
Gumshoeing can be a very lucrative business when the private investigator is
employed by a large company, perhaps looking into fraudulent goings-on among
its employees, or maybe delving into a suspected case of industrial
espionage.
The fee will depend on the size of the corporation; it is not unusual for a
fairly large company to pay a reputable PI with a good track record between
Pounds 800 and Pounds 2,000 a week.
Even more can be earned by the PI who specialises in a particular area of
the commercial sector, such as accounting procedure or computer operations.
Other private detectives who serve the general public - perhaps tracking
down a debtor, tracing a long-lost sweetheart, or ferreting out evidence for
a legal case - may end up less well off.
The fees quoted by these private investigators vary considerably. Some
demand a preliminary payment of about Pounds 150 and have an hourly rate of
around Pounds 20, plus travelling expenses of 30p a mile.
Others are prepared to work on a case for around Pounds 35 a day without a
retainer or without additional charges for transport costs and expenses.
Useful contacts: General Secretary, Association of British Investigators, 10
Banner Hill Road, Kingston-upon-Thames, Surrey KT1 3EP. Institute of
Professional Investigators, 31a Wellington Street, St John's, Blackburn BB1
8AF
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-12180</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGUANAA1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920721
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Management (The Growing Business): The western approach to
gentle persuasion / A look at a scheme for young east European entrepreneurs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In a room at the top of a grand period residence in Queen Anne's Gate,
London, five eastern European young entrepreneurs are considering the
following proposition: 'Selling is a persuasive process where one individual
motivates another individual to buy'.
Aniko Mirtse, aged 22, product manager of a small company in Debrecen,
Hungary, checks her dictionary against the flip-chart. The words
'persuasive' and 'motivates' are causing her some problems, but it is
difficult to tell whether her difficulties are principally linguistic or
ideological.
For Mirtse and her fellow entrepreneurs, the seminar on selling is part of a
British-based project to provide first-hand experience of a western European
market economy. Participants spend a month or two seconded to a small
business in Britain, combining practical experience with training sessions
and social events.
For the sponsoring small businesses the programme may provide, in return, an
entree to eastern European markets at a cost of nothing but their time.
The scheme is organised by a small charity called Enterprise Europe, which
was set up in 1990 by a group of people in their twenties. Pippa Markus,
former press officer for the Institute of Directors and a founding member of
the charity, is now its full-time director.
'A group of us watched the Berlin Wall coming down and felt we wanted to
play some role in the vast changes that were happening. We particularly
wanted to do something practical for people like us, of our age, who were
interested in work and getting on. Some of us also had eastern European
backgrounds,' she says.
The need for technological know-how in eastern Europe is not as acute as the
need for training in, for example, marketing, financial planning,
presentation and customer relations, according to Markus.
Money to fund the scheme is raised from charitable trusts and large
companies, some of which have also paid the full costs of placements.
For small businesses, all the expenses are met by the charity, and
on-the-job training is supplemented by seminars organised by Enterprise
Europe.
Stephen Cowan, director of a sales training group called Focus and a member
of the charity's ruling council, is the volunteer trainer at the Queen
Anne's Gate session.
Trainees are principally from Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia although,
as the programme establishes itself, the intention is to extend the scheme
to Russia, Ukraine, and the Baltic Republics. About 100 applications a week
from prospective trainees land on the London office desk - 14 have passed
through the programme since the second part of last year and further
expansion has been limited by lack of suitable small business placements.
Enterprise Europe prefers trainees to be under 35 and in full-time
employment in their own country, commonly at a pre- or lower management
level - 'the next generation of business leaders in eastern Europe,' says
Markus.
For example, of the present batch battling with 'persuasion' and
'motivation' in the selling seminar, is Marcin Slupski, from Poznan, Poland.
He is 28, and the managing director of a small private company called Inkey,
which sells security systems.
It is Slupski's first visit to the UK and he has spent a month with TDSi, a
company in Dorset which develops access controls. He has been examining ways
the two companies can co-operate, as well as studying TDSi's products and
management.
Richard Benda, from Brno, Czechoslovakia, is 27 and a manager with a trade
fairs and exhibitions company. He has been teamed up by Enterprise Europe
with a mobile exhibition company in Northampton called Business Link. This
placement is an example of the mutual benefits possible under the scheme:
Benda's stay is leading directly to a Czech venture for the company, says
Business Link managing director Anthony Lunch.
'We've increasingly been taking exhibitions abroad and we've had an eye on
eastern European opportunities, but what we needed was a friendly pair of
hands on the other side. Richard Benda has lived very much up to
expectations. We're taking a mobile exhibition to Czechoslovakia in
October,' says Lunch.
Benda has covered the range of Business Link's work from going out and about
selling, to using data bases back at the office. He has networked
ferociously during his month's stay, meeting local authority officials,
Chamber of Commerce chiefs, and dining at the House of Commons with the
local MP. And, reports Lunch, Benda has had a taste of operating in a more
informal, questioning and less bureaucratic environment.
While travel, accommodation costs and other expenses are met by Enterprise
Europe, sponsoring small businesses have to pledge to set aside time
conscientiously for training and supervision.
The time involved should not be underestimated. Says Lunch: 'In a small
company there's no-one to delegate to. It can be difficult to keep the
person busy all the time.'
Meanwhile, back at Queen Anne's Gate it is Benda's turn to puzzle over the
flip-chart; this time the problem is very definitely ideological rather than
linguistic. In front of the trainees is a triangular diagram depicting
Maslow's 'hierarchy of needs'.
Maslow's theory, roughly, is that there are five levels of human need for
satisfaction, starting with basic physiological needs, for example for food
and shelter, and finishing with the need for self-fulfilment, which can
never be completely satisfied. In between the base of the triangle and its
apex are security, social and ego needs. The triangle forms the basis of
marketing and professional selling, explains Stephen Cowan.
Benda earnestly questions Cowan in the coffee break about the morality of
Maslow's theory. Physiological, security and social needs, he has been
taught, should be taken care of by the state, while ego and self-fulfilment
needs are anti-social and should be denied.
However, to Cowan's delight, Benda and his fellow young entrepreneurs are,
by the end of the day, filled with enthusiasm and are practising western
selling techniques on each other. They appear to be fully equipped to
exploit any ego needs that might be burgeoning among customers in their own
countries.
Enterprise Europe, 36 Broadway, London SW1H 0BH. Tel: 071 976 8157
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
