FT  21 JUL 92 / Regional airlines warn of fare rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AIR FARES within the UK and to the rest of Europe may rise if new charges
proposed by the Civil Aviation Authority are brought in, the European
Regional Airlines association warned yesterday.
The CAA is proposing to increase landing and take-off charges to help pay
for better air traffic control equipment. Airlines overflying the UK,
largely from the US, would therefore pay a lower proportion of the CAA's
total income.
Mr Mike Ambrose, director-general of the association, said: 'Airlines using
smaller aircraft providing essential regional services would be worst
affected. They would seek to recover these additional costs through fare
increases.'
The changes also mean greater costs for the CAA and less for the European
air traffic control organisation.
The CAA said the reorganisation of charges was a proposal and it was seeking
responses from airlines. Any changes should be finalised by the end of the
year and in operation from April.
The changes in air traffic control should allow 30 per cent more aircraft to
use the same airspace.
