<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / Gingrich faces trouble in Georgian primary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REPRESENTATIVE Newt Gingrich, the mop-headed right-wing Republican from
Georgia, has long been the scourge of the Democrats in Congress, castigating
their politics, their perks and their personal probity.
But the Democrats are now relishing a sweeter revenge than they could have
dreamed of: Mr Gingrich today faces a tough primary election against a
fellow-Republican who has turned all his taunts against him, branding him as
just another Congressional fat cat.
Mr Gingrich's gadfly tongue so irritated the Democrats who dominate Georgian
politics that they seized the opportunity presented by the 10-yearly
redrawing of Congressional district boundaries to squeeze him out of his
home constituency in the suburbs south of Atlanta, which he held by fewer
than 1,000 votes in 1990.
By way of irony, if the Democrats had been less determined to hurt Mr
Gingrich, who as the minority whip is the second-ranked Republican in the
House of Representatives, they might have stood a better chance of beating
him in the general election in November.
Instead, Mr Gingrich was forced to move to a much more Republican district
in Atlanta's opulent northern suburbs. Although he has been stung by his
Republican primary opponent, former state Assemblyman Herman Clark, he seems
likely to face a much easier battle against a Democrat in November.
Mr Clark's venomous campaign has won national press attention and local
kudos, with its echo of Mr Gingrich's own jibes at Congress.
He has attacked Mr Gingrich for voting for a Congressional pay rise, and for
allegedly writing unfunded cheques on the House bank and abusing Congress
members' free mailing privileges.
He even forced the Congressman to give up his chauffeur-driven limousine.
Mr Gingrich's foes are chuckling to see him running a classic incumbent's
campaign, vaunting his ability to bring money from the federal pork barrel
to the district.
</TEXT>
