FT  21 JUL 92 / Health win for unions in Argentina
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINE union chiefs have won a victory over the government by wresting
back control of the equivalent of Dollars 2bn-Dollars 3bn in funds for
union-managed health schemes.
In exchange, the Peronist-controlled CGT union confederation pledged to
shelve plans for a general strike this month. Both sides signed an accord
committing them to greater social justice and higher benefits for the
country's 3.5m pensioners.
Officials denied concessions were made to the unions that would threaten
economic stability. Mr Domingo Cavallo, economy minister, said wage talks
were constrained by a marketplace thrown open to international competition,
preventing companies granting inflationary wage increases. He had wanted to
allow employees to opt out of union health services and buy private health
insurance.
