<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Costa Rica 'dry canal' may rival Panama -
Plans are under way for a port-rail link across central America
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD ORLEBAR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE financial groups have been courting the Costa Rican government with
offers to build a trading thoroughfare across central America to rival the
Panama Canal. If one is accepted, construction could begin early next year
on two ports and a railway linking the country's Caribbean and Pacific
coasts.
At a meeting on July 10 in the Casa Presidencial, Mr Rolando Lacle, minister
of the presidency, laid down the ground rules for what would be the largest
private sector investment in central America.
Three foreign groups and one from Costa Rica headed by a former president,
Mr Mario Echandi, have so far made proposals for a trans-isthmian link, said
Mr Lacle.
The government would ask for tenders once the legislative assembly had
passed a law allowing the executive to grant concessions to private
companies for infrastructural projects, he added. The bill is expected to
pass next month.
The construction and operation of the ports and railway would be regulated
by a law on free zones, which would grant companies 10 years' grace on
income tax and tax-free imports of capital and intermediate goods. A
detailed environmental impact study would also be required.
Although it is insisted that the route would complement rather than compete
with the Panama canal, the Panamanian authorities have already expressed
concern that the canal would lose traffic. Recently several international
shipping companies protested against a proposed 9.9 per cent rise in toll
charges. A short land bridge would be an increasingly attractive
alternative.
The most talked-about offer is a Dollars 1.2bn proposal by a US consortium,
the Costa Rica Trans Development Corporation, which would lay a 315km
railway along flat, sparsely populated, mostly agricultural land close to
Costa Rica's northern border with Nicaragua.
The proposal is to dredge a deep-water port on the northern Caribbean coast
at Parismina which would be linked by a two-track electric railway to a port
and natural harbour at Cuajiniquil on the Pacific. 'See it as one port
linked by a railway,' said Mr Juan Manuel Rodriguez vice-president of the
consortium.
The dry canal would take at least two and a half years to complete, and a
further two years before investors began to get a return, according to Mr
Rodriguez.
'This is not a restaurant we are opening. This is business for people with
patience and money,' he said.
The new route would be aimed at some of the container cargo shifted by rail
across the US or through the Panama Canal. Four years from now, there could
be a railway moving 750 double-stacked 40-feet containers a day in little
over three hours, according to Mr Rodriguez.
He said the group had the backing of leading shipping and construction
companies. The Boston-based Roy Group which specialises in shipping and
investment was putting together a Dollars 450m long-term equity package with
shipping companies from the Far East, the US and Europe.
The World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank, the latter a big
lender in Costa Rica, have also provided advice to the group but their
assistance would not subordinate the role of private capital, Mr Rodriguez
added. 'Theirs will be a symbolic presence but we welcome it.'
Financing of Dollars 152m for the first year of the plan, to cover an
environmental impact study and initial construction costs, had 'already been
secured'.
The proposed route skirts the Santa Rosa National Park which contains some
of central America's rarest flora and fauna. But according to the natural
resources minister, Mr Hernan Bravo, whose ministry must approve the route,
substantial environmental damage can be avoided. 'The route will be defined
in keeping with environmental parameters,' he said.
The idea of a trans-isthmian link has been well received by the ailing
state-run railway company Incofer which stands to be rejuvenated by the
deal. Incofer subsists on 800m colons (Dollars 60m) from the central
government.
The Trans Development Corporation has suggested the Costa Rican government
and Incofer be granted a share in the consortium.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
